{"title_page": "Dan Patrick (politician)", "text_new": "{{short description|American politician and radio host}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Dan Patrick\n| image = Dan Patrick Texas (cropped).jpg\n| office = 42nd [[Lieutenant Governor of Texas]]\n| governor = [[Greg Abbott]]\n| term_start = January 20, 2015\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[David Dewhurst]]\n| successor = \n| state_senate1 = Texas\n| district1 = [[Texas Senate, District 7|7th]]\n| term_start1 = January 9, 2007\n| term_end1 = January 13, 2015\n| predecessor1 = [[Jon Lindsay]]\n| successor1 = [[Paul Bettencourt]]\n| birth_name = Dannie Scott Goeb\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1950|4|4}}\n| birth_place = [[Baltimore]], Maryland, U.S.\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|Jan Rankin|1975}}\n| children = 2, including [[Ryan Patrick|Ryan]]\n| education = [[University of Maryland, Baltimore County]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])\n| website = {{url|https://www.ltgov.state.tx.us/}}\n}}\n'''Dan Goeb Patrick''' (born '''Dannie Scott Goeb'''; April 4, 1950)<ref name=TexasTribuneStats>{{cite web |url=http://www.texastribune.org/directory/dan-patrick/ |title=State Sen. Dan Patrick |work=The Texas Tribune |series=Elected Officials Directory |accessdate=November 3, 2012}}</ref><ref name=Jan2007TexasMonthlyArticle>{{cite web |url=https://www.texasmonthly.com/politics/here-comes-trouble/ |title=Here Comes Trouble |last=Swartz |first=Mimi |magazine=Texas Monthly |date=January 2007 |accessdate=December 28, 2017}}</ref> is an American radio talk show host, television broadcaster, and politician. He has served as the 42nd [[Lieutenant Governor of Texas|lieutenant governor of Texas]] since January 2015, under [[Greg Abbott]].\n\nOriginally from [[Baltimore]], Maryland, Patrick began his career as a radio and television broadcaster. After forming a chain of sports bars and subsequently going bankrupt, he became a radio host again, this time becoming a conservative commentator. From 2007 to 2015, Patrick was a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] member of the [[Texas Senate]] for the [[Texas Senate, District 7|7th District]], which included a small portion of the city of Houston and several [[Greater Houston|Houston-area]] [[suburb]]s located mostly in northwest [[Harris County, Texas|Harris County]].\n\nPatrick defeated three-term incumbent [[David Dewhurst]] in the [[runoff election|primary runoff]] for lieutenant governor on May 27, 2014.<ref>[http://www.dallasnews.com/news/politics/state-politics/20140527-dan-patrick-wins-gop-nomination-for-texas-lieutenant-governor.ece Dan Patrick wins GOP nomination for Texas lieutenant governor] -Terrence Stutz and Robert Garrett, [[Dallas Morning News]]</ref> He then won the position in the [[2014 Texas lieutenant gubernatorial election|fall general election]]. He was re-elected in 2018, defeating Democratic nominee Mike Collier.\n\n==Early life==\nPatrick was born \"Dannie Scott Goeb\" in [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]], on April 4, 1950.<ref name=\"TheTruth\">{{cite web|url=http://www.danpatrick.org/truth/|title=The Truth \u2013 Name Change \u00bb Dan Patrick for Lieutenant Governor|work=Dan Patrick for Lieutenant Governor|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141104162818/http://www.danpatrick.org/truth/|archive-date=4 November 2014|accessdate=15 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=GOEB 12/20/2002 |date=December 20, 2002  |url=http://www.chron.com/CDA/archives/archive.mpl/obits_3610530/goeb.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130119062432/http://www.chron.com/CDA/archives/archive.mpl/obits_3610530/goeb.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 19, 2013 |newspaper=Houston Chronicle |accessdate=November 3, 2012}}</ref> He was raised in a [[Blue-collar worker|blue-collar]] neighborhood in East Baltimore.<ref name=Jan2007TexasMonthlyArticle />  He is the only child of the former Vilma Jean Marshall (1926\u20132016) and Charles Anthony Goeb (1926\u20132002), who worked at the ''[[Baltimore Sun]]'' for thirty-one years as a newspaper vendor,<ref>''[[San Antonio Express News]]'', April 17, 2014</ref> before he retired in 1984.\n\nPatrick graduated with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in [[English studies|English]] from the [[University of Maryland, Baltimore County]].<ref name=\"TexasStateLegislature\">{{cite web|url=http://www.senate.state.tx.us/75r/senate/members/dist7/dist7.htm|title=Senator Dan Patrick: District 7|work=Members of the Texas State Senate|publisher=Texas Senate|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025132120/http://www.senate.state.tx.us/75r/senate/Members/dist7/Dist7.htm|archivedate=October 25, 2012|accessdate=November 3, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"AudienceOfOne\" /> He is the first member of his family to graduate from college.<ref name=TexasTribuneStats /><ref name=Jan2007TexasMonthlyArticle /> After graduating and embarking on a broadcasting career, he informally changed his name from \"Dannie Scott Goeb\" to \"Dan Goeb Patrick\" in 1977 and legally in 2004, to honor his wife's family and [[Sibling-in-law|brother-in-law]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statesman.com/news/20180217/playing-to-an-audience-of-one-dan-patrick-doesnt-need-your-approval|title=Playing to an audience of one, Dan Patrick doesn't need your approval|last=Walsh|first=Sean Collins|website=Austin American-Statesman|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2014/04/16/ad-dewhurst-attacks-patrick-on-name-change-debts/|title=Dewhurst Ad Attacks Patrick on Name Change, Debts|last=Ramsey|first=Ross|date=2014-04-16|website=The Texas Tribune|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n==Pre-political career==\n===Radio and television===\nPatrick started his first radio job in 1968 at the age of 18.<ref name=\"TheTruth\"/> After college, in 1977, he became a television broadcaster at [[WNEP-TV]] in [[Scranton, Pennsylvania|Scranton]], [[Pennsylvania]]. Patrick later held a similar position at [[WTTG]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], before he became the lead sportscaster<ref name=\"AudienceOfOne\"/> with [[KHOU-TV]] in Houston.<ref name=Jan2007TexasMonthlyArticle /><ref name=\"PartyCrasher\">{{cite magazine |last1=Sweeney |first1=Paul |title=Party Crasher |url=https://www.texasobserver.org/2143-party-crasher-can-houstons-king-of-right-wing-talk-radio-bust-into-the-texas-senate/ |date=February 24, 2016 |magazine=[[The Texas Observer]] |accessdate=December 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAs a broadcaster, Patrick was able to get attention through various stunts, such as painting himself blue in support for the [[Houston Oilers]] and wearing a large [[cowboy hat]].<ref name=Jan2007TexasMonthlyArticle/><ref name=\"RadioPowerful\"/> He became the second most popular TV personality in Houston by 1983,<ref name=Jan2007TexasMonthlyArticle/><ref name=\"RadioPowerful\"/> as well as one of the most well-known,<ref name=\"AudienceOfOne\"/> though surveys also found that he was one of the most disliked.<ref name=\"AudienceOfOne\"/> Patrick also had excellent public speaking skills, which caused him to be nicknamed \"the Silver-tongued Devil.\"<ref name=Jan2007TexasMonthlyArticle/> Patrick left his job at KHOU in the mid-1980s after failing to reach an agreement with the station's new ownership for a long-term contract.<ref name=\"AudienceOfOne\"/>\n\n===Sports bar chain===\nIn November 1983,<ref name=\"AudienceOfOne\"/> Patrick and several investors opened one of the first sports bars in the U.S., which they named Dan and Nick's Sportsmarket.<ref name=Jan2007TexasMonthlyArticle/><ref name=\"RadioPowerful\"/> The bar did well for a time, due to \"the strength of Patrick\u2019s personality\"<ref name=Jan2007TexasMonthlyArticle/> and an oil boom in Houston at the time, and they eventually took ownership of five sports bars in the city.<ref name=Jan2007TexasMonthlyArticle/><ref name=\"RadioPowerful\"/> Patrick's mother was the company bookkeeper. Questions later arose during the 2014 lieutenant governor's race about the [[immigration]] status of one of Patrick's employees, Miguel \"Mike\" Andrade. Patrick and Andrade offered different recollections about Andrade's employment. The matter was raised by one of Patrick's opponents, Jerry Patterson, who questioned Patrick's declared commitment to halt illegal immigration.<ref>\"Patrick: No knowledge of worker's status\", ''[[Laredo Morning Times]]'', February 20, 2014, p. 8A</ref>\n\nWhen the oil boom ended, Houston's economy fell, something which fatally hurt Patrick's sports bar chain.<ref name=Jan2007TexasMonthlyArticle/><ref name=\"RadioPowerful\"/> In 1986, after the sports bars failed, Patrick filed for [[personal bankruptcy]]. In October 1992, the case was closed, discharging several hundred thousand dollars in remaining debts.<ref name=\"Dallas News\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dallasnews.com/news/politics/headlines/20130919-dan-patrick-walked-away-from-large-business-debts.ece|title=Lieutenant governor candidate Dan Patrick knows struggles of going broke|newspaper=Dallas News |date=September 19, 2013|accessdate=May 28, 2014}}</ref> Patrick, who stated it took him 10 years for him and his family \"to regain financial equilibrium,\" has frequently and openly discussed the ordeal and stated how it shaped him as an individual and [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]].<ref name=\"Dallas News\"/>\n\n===Conservative talk radio host===\nSoon after his bankruptcy, Patrick \"reinvented himself.\"<ref name=\"PartyCrasher\"/>  He became a [[conservative talk radio]] host in the 1990s.<ref name=\"Dallas News\"/> He began by buying a four-hour timeslot at [[AM 700]] [[KSEV]] (then called KTBT) in the summer of 1987.<ref name=\"AudienceOfOne\"/> He originally was a [[sports radio]] host, operating out of his remaining sports bar.<ref name=Jan2007TexasMonthlyArticle/><ref name=\"RadioPowerful\"/> However, he was able to take over the radio station in 1988, and he switched to politics shortly afterward.<ref name=Jan2007TexasMonthlyArticle/><ref name=\"RadioPowerful\">{{cite news |last1=Malewitz |first1=Jim |last2=Walters |first2=Edgar |title=Radio Made Dan Patrick Powerful in Texas. And it's Helping Him Stay that Way. |url=https://www.texastribune.org/2017/07/27/radio-made-texas-lt-gov-dan-patrick-powerful-and-its-helping-him-stay-/ |date=July 27, 2017 |work=[[The Texas Tribune]] |accessdate=December 28, 2017}}</ref> He hosted a [[American conservatism|conservative]] radio talk show. The program, ''Dan Patrick & Friends'', was broadcast in the Houston [[media market|radio market]] on KSEV and in [[Dallas]] on [[AM 1160]] [[KBDT|KVCE]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kvceradio.com/host-bios/dan-patrick/ |title=Dan Patrick host bio |publisher=1160 KVCE AM Radio Dallas |accessdate=November 4, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160111111700/http://www.kvceradio.com/host-bios/dan-patrick/ |archive-date= January 11, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://ksevradio.com/hosts/dan-patrick |title=Dan Patrick host information page |publisher=KSEV Radio \u2013 700 AM |accessdate=November 4, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140924111750/http://ksevradio.com/hosts/dan-patrick |archive-date= September 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\nPatrick grew successful and influential through his talk radio career.<ref name=\"PartyCrasher\"/><ref name=\"Dallas News\"/> He earned high name recognition.<ref name=\"PartyCrasher\"/> As a talk radio host, Patrick advocated for [[fiscal conservatism]], [[Evangelicalism|evangelical Christian]] values [[Christian right|on social issues]], and he became a vocal opponent of [[illegal immigration]].<ref name=\"PartyCrasher\"/> He was also known as a [[populist]].<ref name=\"RadioPowerful\"/> Patrick's talk radio career was instrumental to his political rise, including his election and influence in the State Senate and his eventual election as lieutenant governor.<ref name=Jan2007TexasMonthlyArticle/><ref name=\"RadioPowerful\"/> One notable decision Patrick made as the owner of a talk radio station was to sign [[Rush Limbaugh]], who was not well known at the time, to be heard on KSEV in 1989, via [[radio syndication]].<ref name=\"Dallas News\"/> Limbaugh's success as a national talk show host helped raise the popularity of Patrick's radio station.<ref name=\"AudienceOfOne\"/>\n\nBy February 2006, Patrick already owned one radio station.<ref name=\"PartyCrasher\"/> In 2006, Patrick signed a deal to purchase radio station KMGS AM 1160 in [[Highland Park, Texas|Highland Park]], Texas (now [[KBDT]]).<ref>{{cite news |first=Kristen |last=Mack |title=Alvarado looks in Dallas for Latino legal support |url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/metropolitan/mack/3994763.html |newspaper=Houston Chronicle |date=June 23, 2006 |accessdate=November 3, 2012}}{{better source|reason=Source is not clear. Did Patrick create the radio station or did he purchase it? The story talks about another politician joining Patrick in his venture.|date=December 2016}}</ref> By 2013, Patrick was the majority owner of two radio stations, in Houston and Dallas radio markets.<ref name=\"Dallas News\"/> Patrick continued broadcasting after his election as a State Senator, and he continued to own KSEV after his election as lieutenant governor.<ref name=\"RadioPowerful\"/>\n\n===Other===\nPatrick considered running for the [[United States House of Representatives]] in 2004.<ref name=\"TheTruth\"/> According to Patrick, while he was still considering a congressional run he changed his legal name to his air name of ''Dan Patrick'' as candidates could only list their legal name on the ballot rather than a [[pseudonym]].<ref name=\"TheTruth\"/>\n\nIn November 2008, Patrick began work to produce ''The Heart of Texas'', a movie based on a real-life story of two families in [[Simonton, Texas|Simonton]], a small Houston-area city. The movie was released the next year on DVD.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.chron.com/life/hoffman/article/Hoffman-State-Sen-Dan-Patrick-Hollywood-is-1762900.php |title=State Sen. Dan Patrick, Hollywood is calling |newspaper=Houston Chronicle |date=November 19, 2008 |accessdate=November 4, 2012 |last=Hoffman |first=Ken}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://bignews.biz/?id=793436&keys=Heart-Texas-documentary-dvd |title=Press release announcing DVD's release |date=January 31, 2009 |publisher=BigNews.biz |accessdate=November 4, 2012}}</ref>\n\nPatrick proposed a [[boycott]] of [[Bill Maher]]'s television show ''[[Politically Incorrect]]'' over controversial statements made by the comedian following the [[9/11]] terrorist attacks.<ref>[http://www.austinchronicle.com/gyrobase/Blogs/News?subject=oid%3A466283 \"Beyond City Limits: Dan Patrick, Fairness Isn't Enough for Dan\"], ''Austin Chronicle'', April 12, 2007.</ref> Patrick is also frequently at odds with the ''[[Houston Chronicle]]'' and announced a [[boycott]] of that newspaper in April 2004.<ref>Abrahams, Tom. \"Radio talk show host launches boycott against local newspaper\", ''ABC-TV 13 Houston'', April 9, 2004.</ref> He owned a blog called ''Chronically Biased'', which criticized the newspaper.<ref name=Jan2007TexasMonthlyArticle/>\n\n==Texas Senate==\n===First term===\nPatrick was first elected to [[Texas State Senate]]'s [[Texas Senate, District 7|seventh district]] in 2006, winning the [[primary election]] with 68.8% of the vote and the general election with 69.2% of the vote.<ref name=TexasTribuneStats /> His term began on January 9, 2007 with the convening of the [[Eightieth Texas Legislature]].\n\nDuring his first month as a legislator, Patrick introduced Senate Bill 186.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capitol.state.tx.us/tlodocs/80R/billtext/html/SB00186I.htm |title=80(R) SB 186 \u2013 Introduced version \u2013 Bill Text |publisher=Capitol.state.tx.us |date=September 1, 2007 |accessdate=May 1, 2014}}</ref>  If passed, it would have made abortion in Texas illegal should the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] overturn ''[[Roe v. Wade]]''. The bill was co-sponsored by fellow Texas state senators [[Craig Estes]] and [[Glenn Hegar]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.capitol.state.tx.us/BillLookup/History.aspx?LegSess=80R&Bill=SB186 |title=80(R) History for SB 186 |publisher=Texas Legislature Online |accessdate=November 4, 2012}}</ref>\n\nPatrick obtained passage of three Senate bills during his first session.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legis.state.tx.us/Reports/Report.aspx?ID=author&LegSess=80R&code=A1430|title=Texas Legislature Online \u2013 Report|publisher=Legis.state.tx.us|accessdate=January 13, 2015}}</ref> The other four freshmen Senators\u2014Glenn Hegar (32 Senate bills passed), [[Kirk Watson]] (15 Senate bills passed), [[Robert Nichols (Texas politician)|Robert Nichols]] (14 Senate bills passed), and [[Carlos Uresti]] (12 bills passed) \u2013 had previous government experience in other capacities.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.senate.state.tx.us/75r/senate/Members.htm|title=The Texas State Senate: Current Members of the Texas Senate |publisher=www.Senate.state.tx.us|accessdate=January 13, 2015|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19971210182106/http://www.senate.state.tx.us/75r/senate/members.htm|archivedate=December 10, 1997}}</ref>\n\n===Second term===\n[[File:State Sen. Dan Patrick (8428437478).jpg|thumb|Patrick at a 2013 press conference on education]]\nIn the [[Texas elections, 2010|2010 general election]], Patrick was reelected with 86.4% of the vote.<ref name=TexasTribuneStats /> He also endorsed [[Rick Perry]] for re-election in the [[Texas gubernatorial election, 2010|2010 election]].<ref>[http://www.star-telegram.com/news/columnists/bud_kennedy/story/1506661.html]{{dead link|date=May 2014}}</ref> Soon after winning re-election, Patrick announced, and subsequently created, a [[Tea Party movement|Tea Party]] Caucus in the [[Texas state legislature]], which at its creation had 48 legislative members.<ref>Grissom, Brandi (December 16, 2010) \u2013 [http://www.texastribune.org/2010/12/16/sen-dan-patrick-announces-tea-party-caucus/ \"Sen. Dan Patrick Announces Tea Party Caucus\"]. ''The texas Tribune''. Retrieved February 5, 2015.</ref>\n\nW. Gardner Selby, editor of the ''[[Austin American-Statesman]]'''s \"PolitiFact Texas\", listed Patrick as third among the top 10 Republican political influencers in Texas.<ref>(Texas Influencers, August 2010)</ref> Patrick is also listed in ''[[Texas Monthly]]'' as one of the state's most powerful players.<ref>(Power Company, February 2011)</ref>\n\nIn May 2012, acrimony between Patrick and fellow Republican state senator [[John Carona]] was widely reported throughout Texas.<ref name=stateman_spat>{{cite news|url=http://www.statesman.com/news/news/state-regional-govt-politics/emails-provide-rare-glimpse-inside-senate-politi-1/nRnbB/|title=Emails provide rare glimpse inside Senate politics|last=Ward |first=Mike |work=Austin American-Statesman|date=May 7, 2012|accessdate=November 4, 2012}}</ref><ref name=mysa_spat>{{cite news |url=http://www.mysanantonio.com/news/politics/texas_legislature/article/Senators-nasty-emails-refer-to-personal-lives-3540822.php |title=Senators' nasty emails refer to personal lives|last=Fikac|first=Peggy|work=[[San Antonio Express News]]|date=May 7, 2012 |accessdate=May 8, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/article/Senators-Patrick-Carona-make-it-personal-in-3541096.php|work=Houston Chronicle|last=Fikac|first=Peggy|title=Senators Patrick, Carona make it personal in email spat |date=May 7, 2012|accessdate=May 8, 2012}}</ref><ref name=d_spat>{{cite news|url=http://frontburner.dmagazine.com/2012/05/07/gossip-wars-sens-john-carona-and-dan-patrick/|last=Heid|first=Jason|date=May 7, 2012|accessdate= May 8, 2012|work= D Magazine|title=Gossip Wars: Sens. John Carona and Dan Patrick}}</ref> In an email exchange, Patrick accused Carona of spreading false rumors about Patrick's marriage. Carona denied that, and additionally denied having commented on Patrick's sexuality.<ref name=stateman_spat/><ref name=mysa_spat/><ref name=d_spat/> Carona further said to Patrick: \"I've never been shy about sharing my dislike and distrust of you. Put bluntly, I believe you are a snake oil salesman, a narcissist that would say anything to draw attention to himself.\"<ref name=stateman_spat/><ref name=d_spat/> News reports suggest that the feud was motivated by positioning to succeed David Dewhurst as lieutenant governor should Dewhurst have won a seat as U.S. senator, in 2012.<ref name=stateman_spat/><ref name=mysa_spat/>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* Committee on Education (Chair)\n* Committee on Criminal Justice\n* Committee on Finance\n* Committee on Health & Human Services\n* Committee on Intergovernmental Relations\n* Committee on Finance\n** Subcommittee on Fiscal Matters\n** Subcommittee on Public Education Funding\n** Subcommittee on Higher Education Funding\n\n==Lieutenant governor of Texas==\n===2014 campaign===\n{{See also|2014 Texas elections#Lieutenant Governor}}\nOn June 26, 2013, Patrick announced he would challenge incumbent David Dewhurst in the Republican primary for lieutenant governor in 2014.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hamilton |first=Reeve |url=http://www.texastribune.org/2013/06/27/coming-out-swinging-dan-patrick-announces-lt-gov/ |title=Coming Out Swinging, Dan Patrick Announces for Lt. Gov. |work=The Texas Tribune |date=July 7, 2013 |accessdate=May 1, 2014}}</ref> This challenge came despite Patrick's enthusiastic endorsement of Dewhurst in his failed 2012 bid for the U.S. Senate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.redstate.com/irish067/2012/07/27/joann-fleming-slams-patrick-over-dewhurst-endorsement/ |title=JoAnn Fleming Slams Patrick Over Dewhurst Endorsement |publisher=RedState |accessdate=May 1, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Messamore |first=Andrew |url=http://blog.chron.com/texaspolitics/2012/07/dan-patrick-endorses-dewhurst/ |title=Dan Patrick endorses Dewhurst \u2013 Texas Politics |publisher=Blog.chron.com |date=July 26, 2012 |accessdate=May 1, 2014}}</ref> Patrick stated that while he had been planning on retiring from politics after his Senate term ended, he decided to run for lieutenant governor after Dewhurst failed to end fellow State Senator [[Wendy Davis (politician)|Wendy Davis]]'s filibuster of [[Texas Senate Bill 5]] and after Senator [[Jane Nelson]] refused to run herself.<ref name=\"ChristianFirst\"/>\n\nIn his race for lieutenant governor, Patrick was endorsed in July 2013 by [[Mike Huckabee]], the former [[governor of Arkansas]] who ran unsuccessfully for the [[U.S. presidential election, 2008|2008 Republican presidential nomination]]. In 2012, Huckabee had also endorsed David Dewhurst for the U.S. Senate nomination for the seat vacated by [[Kay Bailey Hutchison]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.chron.com/texaspolitics/2013/07/patrick-touts-huckabee-endorsement/|title=Patrick touts Huckabee endorsement, July 23, 2013|publisher=blog.chron.com|accessdate=July 24, 2013}}</ref> Victory went, however, to the Republican [[Ted Cruz]].\n\nAt a candidate forum in [[College Station, Texas|College Station]] in January 2014, Patrick said that he and two other challengers to Dewhurst, [[Jerry E. Patterson]] and [[Todd Staples]], could have sought re-election in their current positions as [[Texas General Land Office|Land Commissioner]] and [[Texas Commissioner of Agriculture]], respectively, but were instead \"putting our positions on the line because we need new leadership. ... An energetic, passionate conservative to lead the Senate.\"<ref name=incollegestation>{{cite news|url=http://www.theeagle.com/news/local/article_eb860364-bdde-543d-9554-7f4622c89351.html|title=Beth Brown, \"GOP lieutenant governor candidates reach out to Bryan-College Station voters,\" January 9, 2013|newspaper=[[Bryan-College Station Eagle]] |accessdate=January 9, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAt the candidate forum, Patrick described education as a key issue in his campaign because of the 25 percent statewide high school drop-out rate, rising to 40 to 50 percent in the inner cities. He stated that \"we do not have a future in the state of Texas if we have half of the next adult population \u2013 majority being Hispanic \u2013 don't have a high school degree.\"<ref name=incollegestation/> Patrick said that as lieutenant governor, he would work to secure the border with [[Mexico]] and to abolish [[sanctuary cities]] and in-state tuition for illegal immigrants. He also called for lowering [[property tax]]es.<ref name=incollegestation/>\n\nPatrick led the four-candidate field in the primary with 550,769 votes (41.5%). Dewhurst followed with 376,196 (28.3%); Staples, with 235,981 (17.8%), and Patterson, 165,787 (12.5%).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://team1.sos.state.tx.us/enr/results/mar04_169_state.htm?x=0&y=218&id=176 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20140305180619/https://team1.sos.state.tx.us/enr/results/mar04_169_state.htm?x=0&y=218&id=176 |url-status=dead |archive-date=March 5, 2014 |title=Republican primary election returns, March 4, 2014 |publisher=enr.sos.state.tx.us |accessdate=March 5, 2014}}</ref> Election watchers did not expect Patrick to get first place.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Hooks|first1=Christopher|title=The Ascendancy of Dan Patrick|url=https://www.texasobserver.org/ascendancy-dan-patrick/|date=March 5, 2014|magazine=[[The Texas Observer]]|accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref> In the runoff election on May 27, Patrick won with 487,829 votes (65.1%), defeating Dewhurst, who had 262,086 votes (34.9%).<ref name=\"Fernandez2014\">{{cite news|last1=Fernandez|first1=Manny|title=Lieutenant Governor Loses Texas Runoff as Tea Party Holds Sway|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/05/28/us/politics/tea-party-favorite-beats-lieutenant-governor-in-texas.html|date=May 27, 2014|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=January 24, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Stutz|first1=Terrence|last2=Garrett|first2=Robert T.|title=Dan Patrick Wins GOP Nomination for Texas Lieutenant Governor|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/local-politics/2014/05/27/dan-patrick-wins-gop-nomination-for-texas-lieutenant-governor|date=May 27, 2014|newspaper=[[The Dallas Morning News]]|accessdate=January 10, 2018}}</ref> Patrick's victory was one of several notable primary victories by [[Tea Party movement]]-aligned Republicans in the election runoff.<ref name=\"Fernandez2014\"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Grissom|first1=Brandi|title=Tea Party Conservatives Win Top GOP Runoffs|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2014/05/28/tea-party-conservatives-win-top-gop-runoff-contest/|date=May 28, 2014|work=[[The Texas Tribune]]|accessdate=January 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Ross Ramsey of ''[[The Texas Tribune]]'', Patrick did not shift to the political middle as the general election approached, contrary to what political candidates typically do.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ramsey|first1=Ross|title=Analysis: Who\u2019s the Establishment, Anyway?|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2018/01/10/analysis-whos-establishment-anyway/|date=January 10, 2018|work=[[The Texas Tribune]]|accessdate=January 10, 2017}}</ref> On November 4, 2014, Patrick won the general election against his state Senate colleague, [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] [[Leticia Van de Putte]] of [[San Antonio, Texas|San Antonio]], to become the lieutenant governor-elect of Texas.<ref name=geresults/> He was swept into office in a Republican landslide that saw the party retain all statewide elected offices for the fifth consecutive election.\n\n===2018 campaign===\n{{See also|2018 Texas elections#Lieutenant Governor}}\nOn January 9, 2017, the day before the 85th Texas Legislature began its session, Patrick announced he would run for re-election in 2018.<ref name=\"Re-Election2018\">{{cite web|last1=Whitely|first1=Jason|title=Lt. Gov. Patrick Announces Re-Election Campaign|url=http://www.wfaa.com/news/politics/lt-gov-patrick-announces-re-election-campaign/384424961|date=January 9, 2017|publisher=[[WFAA]]|accessdate=January 10, 2017}}</ref> He stated his early announcement was in order to dispel rumors that he would challenge Governor [[Greg Abbott]] or U.S. Senator [[Ted Cruz]].<ref name=\"Re-Election2018\"/> Patrick easily won the Republican primary on March 6, 2018, defeating [[Rockwall, Texas|Rockwall]] City Council Member Scott Milder.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McGaughy|first1=Lauren|title=Lt. Gov. Dan Patrick Shreds GOP Challenger, Will Face Mike Collier in General Election|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/2018-elections/2018/03/06/lt-gov-dan-patrick-shreds-republican-challenger-will-face-mike-collier-november|date=March 6, 2018|newspaper=[[The Dallas Morning News]]|accessdate=March 7, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Walsh|first1=Sean Collins|title=Lt. Gov. Dan Patrick Defeats GOP Challenger Scott Milder|url=https://www.statesman.com/news/state--regional-govt--politics/gov-dan-patrick-defeats-gop-challenger-scott-milder/G0fVSSCSLFS9M2aYvb6lbN/new.html |accessdate=May 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to his own campaign, Patrick was active in endorsing and assisting Republican primary candidates in the Texas Senate, including some challengers to GOP incumbents.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jeffers|first1=Gromer, Jr.|title=Already Playing with a Strong Hand, Lt. Gov. Dan Patrick Gambles by Endorsing in GOP Primaries|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/2018-elections/2018/02/21/already-playing-strong-hand-lt-gov-dan-patrick-gambles-endorsing-gop-primaries|date=February 21, 2018|newspaper=[[The Dallas Morning News]]|accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Prazan|first1=Phil|title=Dan Patrick Picks Sides in GOP Primary Races for the Texas Senate|url=https://www.kxan.com/news/local/austin/dan-patrick-picks-sides-in-gop-primary-races-for-the-texas-senate_20180312075314850/1031474849|date=|publisher=[[KXAN-TV]]|accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref> Patrick's favored candidates won nearly all the races where Patrick made intraparty endorsements.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Formby|first1=Brandon|last2=Greene|first2=Sydney|title=GOP State Sen. Craig Estes Ousted; Sen. Bob Hall Defeats Burkett|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2018/03/06/craig-estes-angela-paxton-bob-hall-texas-senate-primary-2018/|date=March 6, 2018|work=[[The Texas Tribune]]|accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref> Later in the year, Patrick donated nearly $175,000 to Texas Senate candidate [[Pete Flores]] in a special election; Flores won the election in an upset, increasing Patrick's chances of keeping a three-fifths GOP majority in the Senate after the 2018 elections.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McGuinness|first1=Dylan|title=Flores Defeats Gallego in Senate District 19|url=https://www.mysanantonio.com/news/local/article/Polls-close-at-7-p-m-in-Senate-District-19-13239398.php|date=September 19, 2018|newspaper=[[San Antonio Express-News]]|accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Svitek|first1=Patrick|title=Republican Pete Flores Upsets Democrat Pete Gallego in Race for Uresti Seat|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2018/09/18/republican-pete-flores-track-upset-race-democratic-friendly-uresti-sea/|date=September 18, 2018|work=[[The Texas Tribune]]|accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Ratcliffe|first1=R.G.|title=The Texas Democratic Party Has Lost the Ability to Sell Its Brand|url=https://www.texasmonthly.com/politics/texas-democratic-party-lost-ability-sell-brand/|date=September 19, 2018|magazine=[[Texas Monthly]]|accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref> Patrick succeeded in maintaining a three-fifths majority in the Senate, though Republican Senator [[Kel Seliger]] was considered a possible swing-vote.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McGaughy|first1=Lauren|title=Democrats Flip Two Texas Senate Seats, Creating Key GOP Swing Vote in the Process|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/2018-elections/2018/11/07/democrats-flip-two-texas-senate-seats-create-key-gop-swing-vote-process|date=November 7, 2018|newspaper=[[The Dallas Morning News]]|accessdate=November 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the November 6 general election, Patrick won re-election to a second term,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Marfin|first1=Catherine|title=Lt. Gov. Dan Patrick defeats Democrat Mike Collier|url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/news/politics/texas/article/With-much-of-early-vote-counted-Lt-Gov-Dan-13368728.php|date=November 6, 2018|newspaper=[[Houston Chronicle]]|accessdate=November 7, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Cunningham|first1=Chelsea|title=Texas Lt. Gov. Dan Patrick defeats Mike Collier for second term|url=https://www.khou.com/article/news/politics/elections/texas-lt-gov-dan-patrick-defeats-mike-collier-for-second-term/285-612126278|date=November 7, 2018|publisher=[[KHOU]]|accessdate=November 7, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Zdun|first1=Matt|last2=Collier|first2=Kiah|title=Gov. Greg Abbott clinches second term as GOP wins closest statewide races in 20 years|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2018/11/06/greg-abbott-lupe-valdez-dan-patrick-justin-nelson-texas-midterm-2018/|date=November 6, 2018|work=[[The Texas Tribune]]|accessdate=November 7, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Morris|first1=Allie|last2=Zelinski|first2=Andrea|title=Gov. Abbott wins re-election as other statewide Republicans claim victory|url=https://www.chron.com/news/politics/texas/article/Gov-Abbott-wins-re-election-as-other-statewide-13369601.php|date=November 6, 2018|publisher=Chron.com|accessdate=November 7, 2018}}</ref> defeating Democratic nominee Mike Collier. He won about 51% of the vote against Collier's 47%.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://enrpages.sos.state.tx.us/public/nov06_331_state.htm?x=0&y=8370&id=374|title=Election Returns|date=November 6, 2018|publisher=[[Texas Secretary of State]]|accessdate=November 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181108030039/https://enrpages.sos.state.tx.us/public/nov06_331_state.htm?x=0&y=8370&id=374|archive-date=November 8, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\n[[File:Donald Trump Dallas 2017.jpg|thumb|200px|Patrick, third from left, attending an October 2017 meeting with U.S. President Donald Trump, Texas Governor [[Greg Abbott]], and [[Federal Emergency Management Agency|FEMA officials]], on [[Hurricane Harvey]] relief and recovery efforts.]]\nPatrick was sworn in on January 20, 2015.<ref name=nextlevel>Lindell, Chuck (January 20, 2015). [http://www.statesman.com/news/news/dan-patrick-snaps-selfies-vows-next-level-conserva/njr2K/ \"Dan Patrick Snaps Selfies, Vows \u2018Next Level\u2019 Conservatism\"]. ''Austin American -Statesman''. Retrieved January 23, 2015.</ref><ref>Fernandez, Manny (January 20, 2015). [https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/21/us/politics/new-texas-governor-greg-abbott-expected-to-continue-on-perrys-path.html \"Texas\u2019 New Governor Echoes the Plans of Perry\"]. ''The New York Times''. Retrieved January 24, 2015.</ref> Soon after assuming office, the [[Texas Senate]] voted to drop the threshold needed to consider a bill from two-thirds to three-fifths, something that Patrick had long supported.<ref name=\"PartyCrasher\"/><ref>Smith, Morgan (January 21, 2015). [http://www.texastribune.org/2015/01/21/change-procedure-senate-democrats-lose-clout/ \"With Change in Procedure, Senate Democrats Lose Clout\"]. ''The Texas Tribune''. Retrieved January 23, 2015.</ref><ref>Koppel, Nathan (January 21, 2015). [https://www.wsj.com/articles/texas-lt-gov-dan-patrick-moves-quickly-to-advance-conservative-agenda-1421883867 \"Texas Lt. Gov. Dan Patrick Moves Quickly to Advance Conservative Agenda\"]. ''The Wall Street Journal''. Retrieved January 23, 2015.</ref> Under Patrick, the Senate enforced procedural rules that had long been ignored.<ref name=\"AudienceOfOne\"/>\n\nMajor legislation that Patrick helped pass during his tenure as lieutenant governor include legalization of [[Campus carry in the United States|campus carry]]<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Jukam|first1=Kelsey|title=The Winners and Losers of the Battle for Campus Carry |url=https://www.texasobserver.org/the-winners-and-losers-of-the-battle-for-campus-carry/|date=June 3, 2015|magazine=The Texas Observer|accessdate=September 29, 2016}}</ref> and [[Open carry in the United States|open carry]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Gov. Abbott signs open carry, campus carry into law|url=http://www.kvue.com/news/state/gov-abbott-signs-open-carry-campus-carry-into-law/152502166 |date=June 13, 2015|work=KVUE|accessdate=September 29, 2016}}</ref> a bill allowing pastors to refuse marrying couples if it violates their beliefs,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Crampton|first1=Liz|title=Abbott Signs \"Pastor Protection Act\" Into Law |url=https://www.texastribune.org/2015/06/11/gov-abbott-signs-pastor-protection-act/|date=June 11, 2015|work=The Texas Tribune|accessdate=September 29, 2016}}</ref> and expanded border security and enforcement measures.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lieutenant Governor Dan Patrick and the Texas Senate Achieved Your Priorities|url=https://www.ltgov.state.tx.us/priorities/lieutenant-governor-dan-patrick-and-the-texas-senate-achieved-your-priorities/|date=June 10, 2015|publisher=Office of the Lieutenant Governor |accessdate=September 29, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Abbott Signs Budget Into Law |url=http://www.twcnews.com/tx/austin/news/2015/06/21/abbott-signs-budget-into-law.html|date=June 21, 2015|publisher=TWC News |accessdate=September 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\nPatrick made legislation prohibiting state or local governments from issuing subpoenas on pastors' sermons a priority in the 2017 session.<ref name=\"SvitekSubpoenas\"/> Governor Abbott signed the bill into law on May 21, 2017.<ref name=\"SvitekSubpoenas\">{{cite news |last1=Svitek|first1=Patrick|title=Abbott Signs Bill Protecting Sermons from Subpoenas |url=https://www.texastribune.org/2017/05/21/abbott-signs-bill-protecting-sermons-subpoenas/|date=May 21, 2017|work=[[The Texas Tribune]]|accessdate=May 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\n===Abortion===\nPatrick opposes [[abortion]] and supported Texas' \"Mandatory Ultrasound Bill\", a bill signed into law in May 2011 by Governor Perry, which requires women seeking abortion to have a [[Medical ultrasonography|sonogram]] of the [[fetus]] taken at least twenty-four hours before the abortion is performed.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n\nPatrick opposes abortion in cases of incest and rape. In January 2014, when he was asked about exceptions to outlawing abortion, Patrick said, \"The only exception would be if the life of the mother was truly in danger\u2026but that is rare.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mystatesman.com/news/news/local/herman-abortion-exceptionalism-in-the-gop-lite-guv/ndC75/#e5ff2779.3657224.735464|title=Herman: Abortion exceptionalism in the GOP lite guv primary |publisher=Mystatesman.com |accessdate=January 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Education===\nPatrick supports increasing the number of [[charter schools]] in the state.<ref name=Nov2010PressRelease />\n\nIn February 2011, Patrick, who at the time was vice chairman of the Texas senate's [[Texas Senate#Committee Structure|Committee on Education]], spoke in favor of cutting an unspecified number of non-teaching positions from the state's public school districts, citing positions such as \"math department supervisors\" or \"curriculum experts\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.texastribune.org/texas-education/public-education/do-texas-schools-spend-too-much-on-administration/ |title=Do Texas Schools Spend Too Much on Administration? |work=The Texas Tribune |date=February 25, 2011 |first=Morgan |last=Smith |accessdate=November 4, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.senate.state.tx.us/75r/senate/commit/c530/c530_81.htm |title=Committee Information for 81st Session's Senate Committee on Education |publisher=Texas State Senate |accessdate=November 4, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026014521/http://www.senate.state.tx.us/75r/senate/commit/c530/c530_81.htm |archivedate=October 26, 2012}}</ref>  At the time, Patrick cited a statistic later determined to be misleading by PolitiFact.com that Texas's 1,200+ public school districts, considered as a group, are the fifth-largest employer in the world.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.politifact.com/texas/statements/2011/mar/11/dan-patrick/dan-patrick-says-texas-school-districts-all-told-a/ |title=Mostly False: Dan Patrick Says Texas school districts are the fifth largest employers in the world. |work=PolitiFact.com |accessdate=November 4, 2012}}</ref>\n\nPatrick is on record as determined to establish [[creationism]] within the public school curriculum in Texas, despite court rulings that such a policy would violate the [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/bad_astronomy/2014/01/29/creationism_and_texas_once_more_into_the_breach_of_education.html|title=Creationism and Texas: Once more into the breach of education.|work=Slate Magazine|accessdate=January 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Patrick pushed to increase Texas teachers' paychecks by $5,000.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Swaby|first1=Aliyya|title=Educators have been skeptical of Dan Patrick. Will they support his teacher pay raise plan?|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2019/02/25/texas-lt-gov-dan-patrick-unpopular-texas-teachers-will-his-teacher-pay/|date=February 25, 2019|work=[[The Texas Tribune]]|accessdate=March 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Swaby|first1=Aliyya|title=Texas teacher pay emerges as a sticking point between House and Senate |url=https://www.texastribune.org/2019/03/05/texas-teacher-pay-emerges-sticking-point-between-house-and-senate/|date=March 6, 2019 |work=[[The Texas Tribune]]|accessdate=March 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Gun laws===\nIn 2019, Patrick called for requiring background checks for gun sales between two strangers.<ref>{{cite news | last1=Axelrod | first1=Tal | title=Texas Lt. Gov: 'Stranger-to-stranger' gun sales should require background check | url=https://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/460297-texas-lt-gov-stranger-to-stranger-gun-sales-should-require-background | date=September 6, 2019 | newspaper=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] | accessdate=September 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine | last1=Brest | first1=Mike | title=Texas Lt. Gov. says he's going to defy NRA and work to close background check loopholes | url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/texas-lt-gov-says-hes-going-to-defy-nra-and-work-to-close-background-check-loopholes | date=September 6, 2019 | magazine=[[Washington Examiner]] | accessdate=September 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Shaw | first1=Adam | title=Texas Lt. Gov. Dan Patrick \u2018willing to take an arrow\u2019 in bucking NRA on background checks | url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/texas-lt-gov-dan-patrick-says-hes-willing-to-take-an-arrow-as-he-bucks-nra-on-background-checks | date=September 7, 2019 | publisher=[[Fox News]] | accessdate=September 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Illegal immigration===\nPatrick opposes [[Illegal immigration to the United States|illegal immigration]]. As a talk radio host, he reserved some of his \"most hard-edged oratory for illegal immigrants.\"<ref name=\"PartyCrasher\"/> Patrick expressed support for [[Arizona SB 1070|Arizona's SB 1070 immigration enforcement law]], and supports passing a similar law in Texas that would allow local law enforcement to ask lawfully-stopped individuals about their immigration status and would make it a state misdemeanor to be present in Texas as an illegal immigrant.<ref name=Nov2010PressRelease>{{cite web|url=http://www.senate.state.tx.us/75r/senate/members/dist7/pr10/p110810a.htm |title=Press Release from the Office of State Senator Dan Patrick: Senator Dan Patrick Files Conservative Agenda |publisher=Texas State Senate |date=November 8, 2010 |accessdate=November 4, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130112152211/http://www.senate.state.tx.us/75r/senate/members/dist7/pr10/p110810a.htm |archivedate=January 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAs Lieutenant Governor, Patrick moved to keep [[National Guard of the United States|National Guard]] troops sent to the Texas-Mexico border during the illegal immigration surge of 2014 indefinitely, rather than until March 2015, as originally planned.<ref name=Natguard>The Associated Press (February 10, 2015) \u2013 [http://dfw.cbslocal.com/2015/02/10/lt-gov-patrick-national-guard-not-leaving-texas-border/ \"Lt. Gov. Patrick: National Guard Not Leaving Texas Border\"]. ''CBS-DFW''. Retrieved February 10, 2015.</ref> Patrick's 2015 budget in the [[Texas Senate]] called for spending $815 million on border security, which he said was more than the previous seven years combined.<ref name=Natguard/> Governor [[Greg Abbott]] signed the measure\u2014for about $800 million\u2014into law.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Garrett|first1=Robert T.|title=Abbott Wields Veto Pen to Trim Nearly $300 Million from Texas Budget |url=http://www.dallasnews.com/news/politics/2015/06/20/abbott-wields-veto-pen-to-trim-300-million-from-texas-budget|date=June 20, 2015|newspaper=[[The Dallas Morning News]]|accessdate=December 19, 2016}}</ref> In a June 2018 interview on [[Fox Business Network]], Patrick estimated that 30 million illegal immigrants lived in the U.S.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Giaritelli|first1=Anna|title=As Many as 30 Million People Live in US Illegally, Says Texas Lt. Gov. Dan Patrick|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/as-many-as-30-million-people-live-in-us-illegally-says-texas-lt-gov-dan-patrick|date=June 22, 2018|magazine=[[The Washington Examiner]] |accessdate=July 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Same-sex marriage and LGBT issues===\nOn February 26, 2014, following a federal court ruling the Texas ban on same-sex marriage unconstitutional, Patrick asserted his position that marriage is a union between one man and one woman. He then further stated his intentions to fight such decisions should he be elected to the Lt. Governor's office.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/DanPatrick/status/438782159138979840 |title=Twitter / DanPatrick: I want to re-emphasize my long |publisher=Twitter.com |date=February 26, 2014 |accessdate=May 1, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/DanPatrick/status/438761650137493504 |title=Twitter / DanPatrick: As Lieutenant Governor I'll |publisher=Twitter.com |date=February 26, 2014 |accessdate=May 1, 2014}}</ref>\n\nPatrick strongly opposed HERO, an unsuccessful [[Houston]] ordinance intended to establish legal protections for gay and transgender residents along with some other classes, as he claimed that the ordinance would lead to sexual predators being freely able to enter women's restrooms.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Driessen|first1=Katherine|title=Patrick takes aim at HERO, mayor |url=http://www.houstonchronicle.com/news/article/Dan-Patrick-takes-aim-at-HERO-mayor-6578348.php|accessdate=May 14, 2016 |newspaper=[[The Houston Chronicle]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Ura|first1=Alexa|title=Bathroom Fears Flush Houston Discrimination Ordinance|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2015/11/03/houston-anti-discrimination-ordinance-early-voting/|date=November 3, 2015|work=[[The Texas Tribune]]|accessdate=May 14, 2016}}</ref> Patrick has stated that if necessary, he would support legislation to require people to use the bathroom that corresponds to the gender listed on their birth certificates.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ward|first1=Mike|last2=Hinchliffe|first2=Emma|title=Patrick Says He Would Support a State Transgender Bathroom Law |url=http://www.houstonchronicle.com/news/politics/texas/article/Patrick-says-he-would-support-a-state-transgender-7377531.php |date=April 26, 2016|newspaper=[[The Houston Chronicle]]|accessdate=May 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHours after the [[2016 Orlando nightclub shooting]], Patrick tweeted a picture of the Bible verse, \"Do not be deceived: God cannot be mocked. A man reaps what he sows. Galatians 6:7.\" An adviser released a statement that the tweet had been pre-scheduled, and the tweet was later deleted.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hamilton|first1=Jessica|title=Texas Lt. Gov. Dan Patrick deletes \"reap what you sow\" tweet after mass shooting at LGBT club|url=http://www.chron.com/news/article/Texas-Lt-Governor-Dan-Patrick-tweets-reap-what-8076147.php |date=June 12, 2016|newspaper=[[The Houston Chronicle]]|accessdate=June 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Blakemore |first1=Allen|title=Statement Regarding Orlando Tragedy and Twitter and Facebook Post |url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/315502915/PR-16-06-12|date=June 12, 2016|accessdate=June 12, 2016}}</ref> Patrick issued a statement on the incident, again stating that the tweet was pre-planned and that \"I didn\u2019t pull down the FB post & tweet because God\u2019s word is wrong. His word is never wrong ... I took it down to stop the hateful comments and the misinformation being spread of God\u2019s message to all of us- straight or gay.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Patrick|first1=Dan|title=My Facebook Statement Regarding This Morning\u2019s Bible Verse Post|url=http://danpatrick.org/facebook-statement-regarding-mornings-bible-verse-post/ |website=danpatrick.org|accessdate=December 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2016, Patrick criticized the [[Obama administration]] after it released a directive stating that all public schools must allow transgender students to use the bathroom and locker facilities that correspond with their identified gender, stating that, on the prospect of the federal government withholding funding for Texas schools for not following the directive, \"he can keep his 30 pieces of silver [and that w]e will not yield to blackmail from the president of the United States.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2016/05/transgender-bathrooms-obama-texas-lieutenant-governor-223159|title=Texas Lt. Gov. Accuses Obama of 'Blackmail' on Transgender Bathrooms|last1=Gass|first1=Nick|date=May 13, 2016 |publisher=[[Politico]]|accessdate=May 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/05/14/us/transgender-bathrooms.html|title=Solace and Fury as Schools React to Transgender Policy|last1=Healy|first1=Jack|last2=P\u00e9rez-Pe\u00f1amay |first2=Richard|date=May 13, 2016|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=May 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://insider.foxnews.com/2016/05/13/tx-lt-gov-dan-patrick-transgender-bathrooms-would-be-end-public-education|title=Texas to Instruct Schools Not to Obey Obama's Transgender Bathroom Decree |accessdate=May 14, 2016|publisher=Fox News Insider}}</ref> In 2017, Patrick strongly advocated for a [[bathroom bill]] that would prohibit transgender students at public schools from using any restroom other than that of their biological sex.<ref name=\"ToughFight\" /> Patrick described the legislation as a \"legislative priority.\"<ref name=\"ToughFight\" /> Patrick encouraged state Senator [[Lois Kolkhorst]] of [[Brenham, Texas|Brenham]] to introduce a [[bathroom bill]] similar to a [[Public Facilities Privacy & Security Act|previous law adopted in 2016]] in [[North Carolina]], and strongly pushed for it at its proposal on January 5, 2017.<ref name=\"ToughFight\">{{cite news|last1=Svitek|first1=Patrick|title=With Bathroom Bill, Texas Lt. Gov. Dan Patrick Plows into \"Tough Fight\" |url=https://www.texastribune.org/2017/01/07/bathroom-bill-patrick-plows-tough-fight/|date=January 7, 2017|work=[[The Texas Tribune]]|accessdate=January 10, 2017}}</ref> [[Speaker of the Texas House of Representatives|Texas House Speaker]] [[Joe Straus]] of [[San Antonio, Texas|San Antonio]], a [[Factions in the Republican Party (United States)#Moderate wing|moderate Republican]], said that the measure is not an important matter for lower chamber.<ref name=\"ToughFight\"/><ref>Bobby Cervantes, \"Bathroom legislation now ready for debate: Bruising battle looms over transgender bill\", ''[[San Antonio Express-News]]'', January 6, 2016, pp. 1, A11</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, Patrick called Democratic presidential candidate Beto O'Rourke \"light in the loafers\", a slur often used to insinuate someone as gay, though O'Rourke is heterosexual. Patrick also called O'Rourke a \"moron.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/houston/article/Lt-Gov-Dan-Patrick-Beto-O-Rourke-is-light-13806867.php|title=Texas Lt. Gov. Dan Patrick: Beto O\u2019Rourke is \u2018light in the loafers\u2019|last=Andrea Zelinski|date=April 30, 2019|website=Houston Chronicle|access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|first1=Zack|last1=Budryk|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/media/441396-texas-lt-governor-calls-beto-orourke-a-moron|title=Texas Lt. Governor calls Beto O'Rourke a 'moron'|website=The Hill|date=April 30, 2019 |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref> Patrick later stated that while he stood by his comments, the insinuation was unintentional.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/DanPatrick/status/1123276995171844096|title=I stand by my remarks on @FoxNews that @BetoORourke is a lightweight with no public policy substance. His views on the border are ridiculous. If anyone took a different meaning from one of my comments, I apologize.  Let me reiterate \u2014 it was not intended.|first=Dan|last=Patrick|date=April 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Marijuana===\nPatrick has advocated against bills that would reduce criminal penalties for marijuana possession. He has expressed skepticism of medical marijuana legalization.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2019/04/30/texas-senate-marijuana-decriminalization-dan-patrick-joe-moody/|title=Texas Lt. Gov. Dan Patrick says Senate won't pass bill to lower penalties for marijuana |last=Tribune |first=The Texas|last2=Samuels|first2=Alex|date=2019-04-30|website=The Texas Tribune|access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref>\n\n===Domestic partner benefits===\nIn November 2012, Patrick asked [[Texas Attorney General|Texas attorney general]] [[Greg Abbott]]'s office to issue an opinion on the constitutionality of government entities providing domestic partner insurance benefits. An [[Texas Proposition 2 (2005)|amendment to the Texas Constitution]] in 2005 limits marriage to heterosexual relationships and prohibits similar, alternative legal arrangements. Patrick did not disclose his own views on [[same-sex marriage]] or [[civil union]]s for same-sex couples. He told the ''[[Houston Chronicle]]'' that his request was prompted by [[Dallas County, Texas|Dallas County's]] November 2012 decision and an [[Pflugerville Independent School District|Austin-area public school district's]] October 2012 decision to join other Texas cities and counties in extending benefits to their unmarried employees' heterosexual or homosexual partners.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/houston/article/Patrick-questions-legality-of-domestic-4004790.php |last=Hassan |first=Anita |date=November 2, 2012 |accessdate=November 4, 2012 |title=Sen. Patrick questions legality of domestic partnership benefits |work=Houston Chronicle}}</ref>\n\n===Statutory rape laws===\nPatrick was interviewed extensively on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s ''[[20/20 (US television series)|20/20]]'' segment \"The Age of Consent: When Young Love Is a Sex Crime,\" defending his position favoring very tough Texas [[statutory rape]] laws. \"While it seems unfair, he was 19, she was 15,\" says Patrick, \"That's the price you pay. Even if you end up getting married.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=John |last=Stossel |author2=Gena Binkley |author3=Andrew G. Sullivan |title=The Age of Consent: When Young Love Is a Sex Crime |url=http://abcnews.go.com/print?id=4400537 |work=ABC News |publisher=ABCNews Internet Ventures |date=March 7, 2008 |accessdate=July 19, 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Confederate monuments===\nPatrick is a strong supporter of maintaining [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] monuments on public display, despite opposition from civil rights groups who consider the statues as a defense of the institution of [[slavery]]. As one of six members of the board that oversees the [[Texas State Capitol]] grounds, Patrick described the need: \"to learn from history all of our history, including events and times that many would like to forget. ... Our goal should be to have a meaningful dialogue for future generations so those moments in our history are not repeated.\"<ref>Allie Morris, \"Austin has a monumental problem: Confederate icons have backing at the Capitol,\" ''San Antonio Express-News,''  August 17, 2017, pp. 1, A6.</ref>\n\n===Coronavirus comments===\n{{further|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Texas}}\nIn an interview with Fox News host [[Tucker Carlson]] on March 23, 2020, Patrick stated that he was willing to risk his life from the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]] if it would avoid an economic shutdown, which he stated would negatively impact subsequent generations. Patrick also stated that he thought many grandparents agreed with him on this.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/489162-texas-lt-gov-grandparents-dont-want-the-whole-country-to-be-sacrificed|title=Texas lt gov: Grandparents 'don't want the whole country to be sacrificed' amid coronavirus closures|first=Aris|last=Folley|date=March 23, 2020|website=The Hill}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/public-health/2020/03/24/texas-lt-gov-dan-patrick-spurns-shelter-in-place-urges-return-to-work-says-grandparents-should-sacrifice/|title=Texas Lt. Gov. Dan Patrick spurns shelter in place, urges return to work, says grandparents should sacrifice|date=March 24, 2020|website=Dallas News}}</ref>\n\n=== Video games ===\nAfter the [[2019 El Paso shooting]], Patrick listed factors that he believed contributed to the shooting, starting off with video games, saying, \"We've always had guns, always had evil, but I see a video game industry that teaches young people to kill.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2019/08/04/dan-patrick-video-games-el-paso-shooting/|title=After El Paso shooting, Texas Lt. Gov. Dan Patrick says video games teach young people \"to kill\"|last=Rocha|first=Alana|date=August 4, 2019|website=The Texas Tribune|language=en|access-date=August 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Presidential politics===\n{{See also|2016 United States presidential election in Texas}}\nPatrick endorsed Texas Senator [[Ted Cruz]] for the [[Republican Party presidential primaries, 2016|2016 Republican presidential primaries]] and served as his Texas [[Ted Cruz presidential campaign, 2016|campaign]] chairman.<ref>{{cite web|title=Texas' Lt. Gov. Now Backing Ted Cruz's Campaign for President|url=http://www.twcnews.com/tx/austin/politics/2015/10/26/lt--gov--dan-patrick-named-texas-chairman-of-ted-cruz-for-president-campaign.html|date=October 26, 2015|publisher=TWC News|accessdate=September 29, 2015}}</ref> After businessman [[Donald Trump]] became the Republican nominee, Patrick endorsed Trump and eventually became the Texas state chairman for [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|his campaign]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Svitek|first1=Patrick|title=Lt. Gov. Dan Patrick Named Trump's Texas Chairman|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2016/09/16/patrick-named-trumps-texas-state-chairman/ |date=September 16, 2016|work=The Texas Tribune|accessdate=September 29, 2016}}</ref> Trump won Texas by 9 percentage points, the closest result since [[United States presidential election in Texas, 1996|1996]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Svitek |first1=Patrick |title=Donald Trump's Shocking Upset Emboldens Texas GOP|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2016/11/09/trumps-impact-texas-gop-unlikely-soon-fade/|date=November 9, 2016|work=[[The Texas Tribune]]|accessdate=December 19, 2016}}</ref> In January 2018, Patrick stated that he considered Presidents Trump and [[Ronald Reagan]] as the two greatest presidents in his lifetime,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wallace|first1=Jeremy|title=Dan Patrick: Trump is Greatest President Since Reagan |url=http://www.chron.com/news/politics/texas/article/Trump-one-of-the-two-greatest-presidents-since-12481441.php|date=January 8, 2018 |newspaper=[[Houston Chronicle]]|accessdate=January 8, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Chang|first1=Julie|title=Lt. Gov. Patrick: Trump Joins Reagan Among Best Presidents|url=http://www.statesman.com/news/state--regional-govt--politics/gov-patrick-trump-joins-reagan-among-best-presidents/0qURfZmAW2EdYyibcbjuVO/|date=January 9, 2018|newspaper=[[Austin American-Statesman]] |accessdate=January 9, 2018}}</ref> and the ''[[Austin American-Statesman]]'' described Patrick as an \"ardent defender\" of Trump.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fikac|first1=Peggy|title=Lt. Gov. Dan Patrick is Trump\u2019s Top Texas Cheerleader |url=http://www.expressnews.com/news/news_columnists/peggy_fikac/article/Lt-Gov-Dan-Patrick-is-Trump-s-top-Texas-12496984.php |date=January 14, 2018|newspaper=[[Austin American-Statesman]]|accessdate=January 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAt a political rally for President Trump on October 17, 2019, Patrick told a crowd of 20,000 that liberals \u201care not our opponents, they are our enemy.\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/18/us/politics/trump-presidency.html|title=On Day 1,001, Trump Made It Clear: Being \u2018Presidential\u2019 Is Boring|last=Baker|first=Peter|date=2019-10-18|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-10-18|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPatrick's first marriage ended in divorce. His second wife is Janetlea \"Jan\" Patricia Rankin, a former [[teacher]]. The couple was married in 1975 and lives in the Houston suburb of [[Cypress, Texas|Cypress]]. They have two children, [[Ryan Patrick|Ryan]] and Shane.<ref name=Jan2007TexasMonthlyArticle /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.patrick.senate.state.tx.us/ |title=The Texas State Senate: District 7 |publisher=Texas State Senate |accessdate=November 4, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026212419/http://www.patrick.senate.state.tx.us/ |archivedate=October 26, 2012}}</ref> Ryan served as a district judge from [[Harris County, Texas]], and swore in his father in 2015, for his term as lieutenant governor of Texas.<ref name=nextlevel/> In July 2017, Ryan Patrick was chosen to be [[United States Attorney|U.S. Attorney]] for the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of Texas|Southern District of Texas]] by U.S. President [[Donald Trump]], and the [[United States Senate]] subsequently confirmed him.\n\n===Religious views===\nWhile growing up, Patrick and his family were \"not very religious.\"<ref name=\"ChristianFirst\">{{cite news|last1=Tilove|first1=Jonathan |title=As Lieutenant Governor, Dan Patrick Remains a 'Christian First'|url=http://www.mystatesman.com/news/state--regional-govt--politics/lieutenant-governor-dan-patrick-remains-christian-first/K53MlGMem1cZSfC2rPe4XJ/|date=April 4, 2015|newspaper=[[Austin American-Statesman]]|accessdate=December 28, 2017}}</ref> After moving to Houston, he and his wife attended a Catholic church,<ref name=\"ChristianFirst\"/> but he joined a Baptist church soon after learning about it.<ref name=Jan2007TexasMonthlyArticle/> Though Patrick was a member of the [[Second Baptist Church Houston]] since 1992, he stated he was not truly a Christian until March 1994, when, on a television-and-radio convention in [[Las Vegas]], he repented of his sins, committed his life to God, and was saved.<ref name=Jan2007TexasMonthlyArticle/><ref name=\"AudienceOfOne\">{{cite news|last1=Walsh|first1=Sean Collins |title=Playing to an Audience of One, Dan Patrick Doesn\u2019t Need Your Approval|url=https://www.mystatesman.com/news/state--regional-govt--politics/playing-audience-one-dan-patrick-doesn-need-your-approval/SCZ3uqoz7sXdstOYvXyxcP/|date=February 16, 2018 |newspaper=[[Austin American-Statesman]]|accessdate=March 6, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"ChristianFirst\"/> After this, Patrick's faith became an important part of his life,<ref name=Jan2007TexasMonthlyArticle/> and he considered going into Christian ministry for a time.<ref name=\"ChristianFirst\"/>\n\nPatrick, an [[Evangelicalism|evangelical Christian]], is a member of various Christian organizations, including [[Fellowship of Christian Athletes]] and the [[International Bible Society]],<ref name=\"VoteSmart\">{{cite web|title=Dan Patrick's Biography|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/57986/dan-patrick#.WFgdA2wzVPY|publisher=[[Project Vote Smart]]|accessdate=December 19, 2016}}</ref> and has served as guest pastor of his church, the [[Second Baptist Church Houston]].<ref name=\"VoteSmart\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Meet Dan|url=http://danpatrick.org/meet-dan/|website=danpatrick.org|accessdate=December 18, 2017}}</ref> He is very outspoken about his Christian faith,<ref name=\"PartyCrasher\"/><ref name=\"ChristianFirst\"/> and he stated in his inauguration speech upon becoming lieutenant governor that \"I respect all faiths and religions, but I am a Christian first, a conservative second and a Republican third, and I praise Jesus for this moment and this day.\"<ref name=nextlevel/> Patrick was baptized in the [[Jordan River]] during a trip to [[Israel]] in 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wise|first1=Hannah|title=Texas Lt. Gov. Dan Patrick Baptized in Jordan River During Visit to Israel|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/politics/2016/05/01/texas-lt-gov-dan-patrick-baptized-in-jordan-river-during-visit-to-israel|date=May 1, 2016|newspaper=[[The Dallas Morning News]]|accessdate=February 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n===2014===\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title=Texas lieutenant gubernatorial election, 2014<ref name=geresults>{{cite web|url=https://team1.sos.state.tx.us/enr/results/nov04_175_state.htm |title=Office of the Secretary of State 2014 General Election Election Night Returns |publisher=Texas Secretary of State |accessdate=December 29, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141105175126/https://team1.sos.state.tx.us/enr/results/nov04_175_state.htm |archivedate=November 5, 2014 }}</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Dan Patrick\n  |votes      = 2,718,406\n  |percentage = 58.13\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = [[Leticia Van de Putte]]\n  |votes      = 1,810,720\n  |percentage = 38.72\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = Libertarian Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Robert Butler\n  |votes      = 119,581\n  |percentage = 2.55\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = Green Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Chandra Courtney\n  |votes      = 27,651\n  |percentage = 0.59\n}}\n{{Election box majority no change\n  |votes      = 907,686\n  |percentage = 19.41%\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n  |votes      = 4,676,358\n  |percentage = 100\n}}\n{{Election box turnout no change\n  |votes      =\n  |percentage = 33.34\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link no change\n  |winner     = Republican Party (United States)\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = Republican primary runoff results, May 27, 2014:  [[List of lieutenant governors of Texas|Lieutenant Governor of Texas]]<ref>[https://team1.sos.state.tx.us/enr/results/may27_173_state.htm]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140529052345/https://team1.sos.state.tx.us/enr/results/may27_173_state.htm |date=May 29, 2014 }}</ref> \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = '''Dan Patrick'''\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = '''488,150'''\n| percentage = '''65.04'''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = David Dewhurst \u2013 Incumbent\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = 262,303\n| percentage = 34.95\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 750,453\n| percentage = 100\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Republican primary results, March 4, 2014: Lieutenant Governor of Texas\n|-\n!Party\n!Candidate\n!Votes\n!%\n|-\n|Republican\n|'''Dan Patrick'''\n|'''552,692'''\n|'''41.43'''\n|-\n|Republican\n|'''David Dewhurst - Incumbent'''\n|'''377,856'''\n|'''28.33'''\n|-\n|Republican\n|Todd Staples\n|236,949\n|17.76\n|-\n|Republican\n|Jerry Patterson\n|166,399\n|12.47\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |'''Total votes'''\n|'''1,333,896'''\n|'''100.00'''\n|}\n\n===2010===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"5\" |Texas general election, 2010: Senate District 7\n|-\n!Party\n!Candidate\n!Votes\n!%\n!\u00b1\n|-\n|Republican\n|'''Dan Patrick - Incumbent'''\n|'''184,704'''\n|'''86.41'''\n|\n|-\n|Libertarian\n|Lee Coughran\n|29,048\n|13.59\n|\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |'''Majority'''\n|155,656\n|72.82\n|\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |'''Turnout'''\n|213,752\n|\n|\n|-\n| colspan=\"5\" |Republican '''hold'''\n|}\n\n===2006===\n{{Election box begin\n| title=[[Texas general election, 2006]]:  [[Texas Senate, District 7|Senate District 7]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://elections.sos.state.tx.us/elchist127_state.htm |title=2006 General Election |accessdate=December 23, 2006 |publisher=Office of the Secretary of State (Texas)}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n|  party= Republican Party (US)\n|  candidate  = Dan Patrick\n|  votes      = 118,067\n|  percentage = 69.19\n|  change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n|  party= Democratic Party (US)\n|  candidate  = F. Michael Kubosh\n|  votes      = 52,586\n|  percentage = 30.81\n|  change     =\n}}\n{{Election box majority\n|  votes      = 65,481\n|  percentage = 38.37\n|  change     =\n}}\n{{Election box turnout\n|  votes      = 170,653\n|  percentage =\n|  change     =\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link no swing\n|  winner     = Republican Party (US)\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n{{Election box begin no party\n| title=[[United States Republican Party|Republican]] primary, 2006: [[Texas Senate, District 7|Senate District 7]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://elections.sos.state.tx.us/elchist118_state.htm |title=2006 Republican Party Primary Election |accessdate=December 23, 2006 |publisher=Office of the Secretary of State (Texas)}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box candidate no party with winner\n|  winner     =\n|  candidate  = Mark Ellis\n|  votes      = 2,545\n|  percentage = 6.07\n|  change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate no party with winner\n|  winner     =\n|  candidate  = Peggy Hamric\n|  votes      = 6,900\n|  percentage = 16.45\n|  change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate no party with winner\n|  winner     =\n|  candidate  = [[Joe Nixon]]\n|  votes      = 3,629\n|  percentage = 8.65\n|  change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate no party with winner\n|  winner     = \u2713\n|  candidate  = Dan Patrick\n|  votes      = 28,860\n|  percentage = 68.82\n|  change     =\n}}\n{{Election box turnout no party\n|  votes      = 41,934\n|  percentage =\n|  change     =\n}}\n{{election box end}}\n\n==Works==\n* Patrick, Dan (2002). ''The Second Most Important Book You Will Ever Read: A Personal Challenge to Read the Bible'', Publisher: [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|Thomas Nelson, Inc.]], {{ISBN|0-7852-6286-5}}\n* ''The Heart of Texas'' (film). [http://www.heartoftexasthemovie.com link title]. Dan Patrick, Executive Producer. 2009 Plaid Shirt Pictures and Media Tech, Inc.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Maryland|Texas|Politics|Conservatism|Television|Radio|Christianity}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n* [https://www.ltgov.state.tx.us/ Lieutenant Governor of Texas] Official state website\n* [https://www.danpatrick.org/ Dan Patrick] ''campaign site''\n* {{CongLinks | congbio= | votesmart=57986 | fec= | congress= }}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080828081700/http://www.thevoiceoftexas.org/ The Voice of Texas Foundation] Dan Patrick for Texas Governor PAC\n* [http://www.texasobserver.org/article.php?aid=2143 ''Texas Observer'' article, \"Party Crasher\"]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070716203603/http://the.ricethresher.org/opinion/2007/01/12/dan_patrick_texas_senator ''Rice Thresher'' article, \"Shock-jock senator tunes out left, turns off right\"]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060324161626/http://www.clouttexas.com/ CLOUT] Patrick's political organization.\n* [http://www.lonestartimes.com Lone Star Times], Weblog launched by Patrick, but no longer owned by or formally affiliated with him.\n* [http://www.chronicallybiased.com/ Chronically Biased], a website critical of the ''[[Houston Chronicle]]'' maintained by Patrick until 2005\n*{{C-SPAN|Dan Patrick 02}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-tx-sen}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jon Lindsay]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[Texas Senate]]<br />from the [[Texas Senate, District 7|7th]] district|years=2007\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Paul Bettencourt]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Dewhurst]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Lieutenant Governor of Texas]]|years=2015\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Current Texas statewide political officials}}\n{{Current U.S. Lieutenant Governors}}\n{{Current U.S. State Senate Presidents}}\n{{Governors of Texas |expanded=Lt. Governors}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Patrick, Dan (Texas politician)}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Baptists]]\n[[Category:Activists from Texas]]\n[[Category:American anti\u2013illegal immigration activists]]\n[[Category:American broadcasters]]\n[[Category:American Christian writers]]\n[[Category:American conservative talk radio hosts]]\n[[Category:American evangelicals]]\n[[Category:American television personalities]]\n[[Category:Baptists from Texas]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Texas]]\n[[Category:Lieutenant Governors of Texas]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Houston]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Baltimore]]\n[[Category:Tea Party movement activists]]\n[[Category:Texas Republicans]]\n[[Category:Texas state senators]]\n[[Category:University of Maryland, Baltimore County alumni]]\n[[Category:Baptists from Maryland]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American politician and radio host}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Dan Patrick\n| image = Dan Patrick Texas (cropped).jpg\n| office = 42nd [[Lieutenant Governor of Texas]]\n| governor = [[Greg Abbott]]\n| term_start = January 20, 2015\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[David Dewhurst]]\n| successor = \n| state_senate1 = Texas\n| district1 = [[Texas Senate, District 7|7th]]\n| term_start1 = January 9, 2007\n| term_end1 = January 13, 2015\n| predecessor1 = [[Jon Lindsay]]\n| successor1 = [[Paul Bettencourt]]\n| birth_name = Dannie Scott Goeb\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1950|4|4}}\n| birth_place = [[Baltimore]], Maryland, U.S.\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|Jan Rankin|1975}}\n| children = 2, including [[Ryan Patrick|Ryan]]\n| education = [[University of Maryland, Baltimore County]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])\n| website = {{url|https://www.ltgov.state.tx.us/}}\n}}\n'''Dan Goeb Patrick''' (born '''Dannie Scott Goeb'''; April 4, 1950)<ref name=TexasTribuneStats>{{cite web |url=http://www.texastribune.org/directory/dan-patrick/ |title=State Sen. Dan Patrick |work=The Texas Tribune |series=Elected Officials Directory |accessdate=November 3, 2012}}</ref><ref name=Jan2007TexasMonthlyArticle>{{cite web |url=https://www.texasmonthly.com/politics/here-comes-trouble/ |title=Here Comes Trouble |last=Swartz |first=Mimi |magazine=Texas Monthly |date=January 2007 |accessdate=December 28, 2017}}</ref> is an American radio talk show host, television broadcaster, and politician. He has served as the 42nd [[Lieutenant Governor of Texas|lieutenant governor of Texas]] since January 2015, under [[Greg Abbott]].\n\nOriginally from [[Baltimore]], Maryland, Patrick began his career as a radio and television broadcaster. After forming a chain of sports bars and subsequently going bankrupt, he became a radio host again, this time becoming a conservative commentator. From 2007 to 2015, Patrick was a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] member of the [[Texas Senate]] for the [[Texas Senate, District 7|7th District]], which included a small portion of the city of Houston and several [[Greater Houston|Houston-area]] [[suburb]]s located mostly in northwest [[Harris County, Texas|Harris County]].\n\nPatrick defeated three-term incumbent [[David Dewhurst]] in the [[runoff election|primary runoff]] for lieutenant governor on May 27, 2014.<ref>[http://www.dallasnews.com/news/politics/state-politics/20140527-dan-patrick-wins-gop-nomination-for-texas-lieutenant-governor.ece Dan Patrick wins GOP nomination for Texas lieutenant governor] -Terrence Stutz and Robert Garrett, [[Dallas Morning News]]</ref> He then won the position in the [[2014 Texas lieutenant gubernatorial election|fall general election]]. He was re-elected in 2018, defeating Democratic nominee Mike Collier.\n\n==Early life==\nPatrick was born \"Dannie Scott Goeb\" in [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]], on April 4, 1950.<ref name=\"TheTruth\">{{cite web|url=http://www.danpatrick.org/truth/|title=The Truth \u2013 Name Change \u00bb Dan Patrick for Lieutenant Governor|work=Dan Patrick for Lieutenant Governor|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141104162818/http://www.danpatrick.org/truth/|archive-date=4 November 2014|accessdate=15 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=GOEB 12/20/2002 |date=December 20, 2002  |url=http://www.chron.com/CDA/archives/archive.mpl/obits_3610530/goeb.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130119062432/http://www.chron.com/CDA/archives/archive.mpl/obits_3610530/goeb.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 19, 2013 |newspaper=Houston Chronicle |accessdate=November 3, 2012}}</ref> He was raised in a [[Blue-collar worker|blue-collar]] neighborhood in East Baltimore.<ref name=Jan2007TexasMonthlyArticle />  He is the only child of the former Vilma Jean Marshall (1926\u20132016) and Charles Anthony Goeb (1926\u20132002), who worked at the ''[[Baltimore Sun]]'' for thirty-one years as a newspaper vendor,<ref>''[[San Antonio Express News]]'', April 17, 2014</ref> before he retired in 1984.\n\nPatrick graduated with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in [[English studies|English]] from the [[University of Maryland, Baltimore County]].<ref name=\"TexasStateLegislature\">{{cite web|url=http://www.senate.state.tx.us/75r/senate/members/dist7/dist7.htm|title=Senator Dan Patrick: District 7|work=Members of the Texas State Senate|publisher=Texas Senate|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025132120/http://www.senate.state.tx.us/75r/senate/Members/dist7/Dist7.htm|archivedate=October 25, 2012|accessdate=November 3, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"AudienceOfOne\" /> He is the first member of his family to graduate from college.<ref name=TexasTribuneStats /><ref name=Jan2007TexasMonthlyArticle /> After graduating and embarking on a professional career, he informally changed his name from \"Dannie Scott Goeb\" to \"Dan Goeb Patrick\" in 1977 and legally in 2004, to honor his wife's family and [[Sibling-in-law|brother-in-law]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statesman.com/news/20180217/playing-to-an-audience-of-one-dan-patrick-doesnt-need-your-approval|title=Playing to an audience of one, Dan Patrick doesn't need your approval|last=Walsh|first=Sean Collins|website=Austin American-Statesman|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2014/04/16/ad-dewhurst-attacks-patrick-on-name-change-debts/|title=Dewhurst Ad Attacks Patrick on Name Change, Debts|last=Ramsey|first=Ross|date=2014-04-16|website=The Texas Tribune|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n==Pre-political career==\n===Radio and television===\nPatrick started his first radio job in 1968 at the age of 18.<ref name=\"TheTruth\"/> After college, in 1977, he became a television broadcaster at [[WNEP-TV]] in [[Scranton, Pennsylvania|Scranton]], [[Pennsylvania]]. Patrick later held a similar position at [[WTTG]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], before he became the lead sportscaster<ref name=\"AudienceOfOne\"/> with [[KHOU-TV]] in Houston.<ref name=Jan2007TexasMonthlyArticle /><ref name=\"PartyCrasher\">{{cite magazine |last1=Sweeney |first1=Paul |title=Party Crasher |url=https://www.texasobserver.org/2143-party-crasher-can-houstons-king-of-right-wing-talk-radio-bust-into-the-texas-senate/ |date=February 24, 2016 |magazine=[[The Texas Observer]] |accessdate=December 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAs a broadcaster, Patrick was able to get attention through various stunts, such as painting himself blue in support for the [[Houston Oilers]] and wearing a large [[cowboy hat]].<ref name=Jan2007TexasMonthlyArticle/><ref name=\"RadioPowerful\"/> He became the second most popular TV personality in Houston by 1983,<ref name=Jan2007TexasMonthlyArticle/><ref name=\"RadioPowerful\"/> as well as one of the most well-known,<ref name=\"AudienceOfOne\"/> though surveys also found that he was one of the most disliked.<ref name=\"AudienceOfOne\"/> Patrick also had excellent public speaking skills, which caused him to be nicknamed \"the Silver-tongued Devil.\"<ref name=Jan2007TexasMonthlyArticle/> Patrick left his job at KHOU in the mid-1980s after failing to reach an agreement with the station's new ownership for a long-term contract.<ref name=\"AudienceOfOne\"/>\n\n===Sports bar chain===\nIn November 1983,<ref name=\"AudienceOfOne\"/> Patrick and several investors opened one of the first sports bars in the U.S., which they named Dan and Nick's Sportsmarket.<ref name=Jan2007TexasMonthlyArticle/><ref name=\"RadioPowerful\"/> The bar did well for a time, due to \"the strength of Patrick\u2019s personality\"<ref name=Jan2007TexasMonthlyArticle/> and an oil boom in Houston at the time, and they eventually took ownership of five sports bars in the city.<ref name=Jan2007TexasMonthlyArticle/><ref name=\"RadioPowerful\"/> Patrick's mother was the company bookkeeper. Questions later arose during the 2014 lieutenant governor's race about the [[immigration]] status of one of Patrick's employees, Miguel \"Mike\" Andrade. Patrick and Andrade offered different recollections about Andrade's employment. The matter was raised by one of Patrick's opponents, Jerry Patterson, who questioned Patrick's declared commitment to halt illegal immigration.<ref>\"Patrick: No knowledge of worker's status\", ''[[Laredo Morning Times]]'', February 20, 2014, p. 8A</ref>\n\nWhen the oil boom ended, Houston's economy fell, something which fatally hurt Patrick's sports bar chain.<ref name=Jan2007TexasMonthlyArticle/><ref name=\"RadioPowerful\"/> In 1986, after the sports bars failed, Patrick filed for [[personal bankruptcy]]. In October 1992, the case was closed, discharging several hundred thousand dollars in remaining debts.<ref name=\"Dallas News\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dallasnews.com/news/politics/headlines/20130919-dan-patrick-walked-away-from-large-business-debts.ece|title=Lieutenant governor candidate Dan Patrick knows struggles of going broke|newspaper=Dallas News |date=September 19, 2013|accessdate=May 28, 2014}}</ref> Patrick, who stated it took him 10 years for him and his family \"to regain financial equilibrium,\" has frequently and openly discussed the ordeal and stated how it shaped him as an individual and [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]].<ref name=\"Dallas News\"/>\n\n===Conservative talk radio host===\nSoon after his bankruptcy, Patrick \"reinvented himself.\"<ref name=\"PartyCrasher\"/>  He became a [[conservative talk radio]] host in the 1990s.<ref name=\"Dallas News\"/> He began by buying a four-hour timeslot at [[AM 700]] [[KSEV]] (then called KTBT) in the summer of 1987.<ref name=\"AudienceOfOne\"/> He originally was a [[sports radio]] host, operating out of his remaining sports bar.<ref name=Jan2007TexasMonthlyArticle/><ref name=\"RadioPowerful\"/> However, he was able to take over the radio station in 1988, and he switched to politics shortly afterward.<ref name=Jan2007TexasMonthlyArticle/><ref name=\"RadioPowerful\">{{cite news |last1=Malewitz |first1=Jim |last2=Walters |first2=Edgar |title=Radio Made Dan Patrick Powerful in Texas. And it's Helping Him Stay that Way. |url=https://www.texastribune.org/2017/07/27/radio-made-texas-lt-gov-dan-patrick-powerful-and-its-helping-him-stay-/ |date=July 27, 2017 |work=[[The Texas Tribune]] |accessdate=December 28, 2017}}</ref> He hosted a [[American conservatism|conservative]] radio talk show. The program, ''Dan Patrick & Friends'', was broadcast in the Houston [[media market|radio market]] on KSEV and in [[Dallas]] on [[AM 1160]] [[KBDT|KVCE]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kvceradio.com/host-bios/dan-patrick/ |title=Dan Patrick host bio |publisher=1160 KVCE AM Radio Dallas |accessdate=November 4, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160111111700/http://www.kvceradio.com/host-bios/dan-patrick/ |archive-date= January 11, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://ksevradio.com/hosts/dan-patrick |title=Dan Patrick host information page |publisher=KSEV Radio \u2013 700 AM |accessdate=November 4, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140924111750/http://ksevradio.com/hosts/dan-patrick |archive-date= September 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\nPatrick grew successful and influential through his talk radio career.<ref name=\"PartyCrasher\"/><ref name=\"Dallas News\"/> He earned high name recognition.<ref name=\"PartyCrasher\"/> As a talk radio host, Patrick advocated for [[fiscal conservatism]], [[Evangelicalism|evangelical Christian]] values [[Christian right|on social issues]], and he became a vocal opponent of [[illegal immigration]].<ref name=\"PartyCrasher\"/> He was also known as a [[populist]].<ref name=\"RadioPowerful\"/> Patrick's talk radio career was instrumental to his political rise, including his election and influence in the State Senate and his eventual election as lieutenant governor.<ref name=Jan2007TexasMonthlyArticle/><ref name=\"RadioPowerful\"/> One notable decision Patrick made as the owner of a talk radio station was to sign [[Rush Limbaugh]], who was not well known at the time, to be heard on KSEV in 1989, via [[radio syndication]].<ref name=\"Dallas News\"/> Limbaugh's success as a national talk show host helped raise the popularity of Patrick's radio station.<ref name=\"AudienceOfOne\"/>\n\nBy February 2006, Patrick already owned one radio station.<ref name=\"PartyCrasher\"/> In 2006, Patrick signed a deal to purchase radio station KMGS AM 1160 in [[Highland Park, Texas|Highland Park]], Texas (now [[KBDT]]).<ref>{{cite news |first=Kristen |last=Mack |title=Alvarado looks in Dallas for Latino legal support |url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/metropolitan/mack/3994763.html |newspaper=Houston Chronicle |date=June 23, 2006 |accessdate=November 3, 2012}}{{better source|reason=Source is not clear. Did Patrick create the radio station or did he purchase it? The story talks about another politician joining Patrick in his venture.|date=December 2016}}</ref> By 2013, Patrick was the majority owner of two radio stations, in Houston and Dallas radio markets.<ref name=\"Dallas News\"/> Patrick continued broadcasting after his election as a State Senator, and he continued to own KSEV after his election as lieutenant governor.<ref name=\"RadioPowerful\"/>\n\n===Other===\nPatrick considered running for the [[United States House of Representatives]] in 2004.<ref name=\"TheTruth\"/> According to Patrick, while he was still considering a congressional run he changed his legal name to his air name of ''Dan Patrick'' as candidates could only list their legal name on the ballot rather than a [[pseudonym]].<ref name=\"TheTruth\"/>\n\nIn November 2008, Patrick began work to produce ''The Heart of Texas'', a movie based on a real-life story of two families in [[Simonton, Texas|Simonton]], a small Houston-area city. The movie was released the next year on DVD.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.chron.com/life/hoffman/article/Hoffman-State-Sen-Dan-Patrick-Hollywood-is-1762900.php |title=State Sen. Dan Patrick, Hollywood is calling |newspaper=Houston Chronicle |date=November 19, 2008 |accessdate=November 4, 2012 |last=Hoffman |first=Ken}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://bignews.biz/?id=793436&keys=Heart-Texas-documentary-dvd |title=Press release announcing DVD's release |date=January 31, 2009 |publisher=BigNews.biz |accessdate=November 4, 2012}}</ref>\n\nPatrick proposed a [[boycott]] of [[Bill Maher]]'s television show ''[[Politically Incorrect]]'' over controversial statements made by the comedian following the [[9/11]] terrorist attacks.<ref>[http://www.austinchronicle.com/gyrobase/Blogs/News?subject=oid%3A466283 \"Beyond City Limits: Dan Patrick, Fairness Isn't Enough for Dan\"], ''Austin Chronicle'', April 12, 2007.</ref> Patrick is also frequently at odds with the ''[[Houston Chronicle]]'' and announced a [[boycott]] of that newspaper in April 2004.<ref>Abrahams, Tom. \"Radio talk show host launches boycott against local newspaper\", ''ABC-TV 13 Houston'', April 9, 2004.</ref> He owned a blog called ''Chronically Biased'', which criticized the newspaper.<ref name=Jan2007TexasMonthlyArticle/>\n\n==Texas Senate==\n===First term===\nPatrick was first elected to [[Texas State Senate]]'s [[Texas Senate, District 7|seventh district]] in 2006, winning the [[primary election]] with 68.8% of the vote and the general election with 69.2% of the vote.<ref name=TexasTribuneStats /> His term began on January 9, 2007 with the convening of the [[Eightieth Texas Legislature]].\n\nDuring his first month as a legislator, Patrick introduced Senate Bill 186.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capitol.state.tx.us/tlodocs/80R/billtext/html/SB00186I.htm |title=80(R) SB 186 \u2013 Introduced version \u2013 Bill Text |publisher=Capitol.state.tx.us |date=September 1, 2007 |accessdate=May 1, 2014}}</ref>  If passed, it would have made abortion in Texas illegal should the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] overturn ''[[Roe v. Wade]]''. The bill was co-sponsored by fellow Texas state senators [[Craig Estes]] and [[Glenn Hegar]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.capitol.state.tx.us/BillLookup/History.aspx?LegSess=80R&Bill=SB186 |title=80(R) History for SB 186 |publisher=Texas Legislature Online |accessdate=November 4, 2012}}</ref>\n\nPatrick obtained passage of three Senate bills during his first session.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legis.state.tx.us/Reports/Report.aspx?ID=author&LegSess=80R&code=A1430|title=Texas Legislature Online \u2013 Report|publisher=Legis.state.tx.us|accessdate=January 13, 2015}}</ref> The other four freshmen Senators\u2014Glenn Hegar (32 Senate bills passed), [[Kirk Watson]] (15 Senate bills passed), [[Robert Nichols (Texas politician)|Robert Nichols]] (14 Senate bills passed), and [[Carlos Uresti]] (12 bills passed) \u2013 had previous government experience in other capacities.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.senate.state.tx.us/75r/senate/Members.htm|title=The Texas State Senate: Current Members of the Texas Senate |publisher=www.Senate.state.tx.us|accessdate=January 13, 2015|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19971210182106/http://www.senate.state.tx.us/75r/senate/members.htm|archivedate=December 10, 1997}}</ref>\n\n===Second term===\n[[File:State Sen. Dan Patrick (8428437478).jpg|thumb|Patrick at a 2013 press conference on education]]\nIn the [[Texas elections, 2010|2010 general election]], Patrick was reelected with 86.4% of the vote.<ref name=TexasTribuneStats /> He also endorsed [[Rick Perry]] for re-election in the [[Texas gubernatorial election, 2010|2010 election]].<ref>[http://www.star-telegram.com/news/columnists/bud_kennedy/story/1506661.html]{{dead link|date=May 2014}}</ref> Soon after winning re-election, Patrick announced, and subsequently created, a [[Tea Party movement|Tea Party]] Caucus in the [[Texas state legislature]], which at its creation had 48 legislative members.<ref>Grissom, Brandi (December 16, 2010) \u2013 [http://www.texastribune.org/2010/12/16/sen-dan-patrick-announces-tea-party-caucus/ \"Sen. Dan Patrick Announces Tea Party Caucus\"]. ''The texas Tribune''. Retrieved February 5, 2015.</ref>\n\nW. Gardner Selby, editor of the ''[[Austin American-Statesman]]'''s \"PolitiFact Texas\", listed Patrick as third among the top 10 Republican political influencers in Texas.<ref>(Texas Influencers, August 2010)</ref> Patrick is also listed in ''[[Texas Monthly]]'' as one of the state's most powerful players.<ref>(Power Company, February 2011)</ref>\n\nIn May 2012, acrimony between Patrick and fellow Republican state senator [[John Carona]] was widely reported throughout Texas.<ref name=stateman_spat>{{cite news|url=http://www.statesman.com/news/news/state-regional-govt-politics/emails-provide-rare-glimpse-inside-senate-politi-1/nRnbB/|title=Emails provide rare glimpse inside Senate politics|last=Ward |first=Mike |work=Austin American-Statesman|date=May 7, 2012|accessdate=November 4, 2012}}</ref><ref name=mysa_spat>{{cite news |url=http://www.mysanantonio.com/news/politics/texas_legislature/article/Senators-nasty-emails-refer-to-personal-lives-3540822.php |title=Senators' nasty emails refer to personal lives|last=Fikac|first=Peggy|work=[[San Antonio Express News]]|date=May 7, 2012 |accessdate=May 8, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/article/Senators-Patrick-Carona-make-it-personal-in-3541096.php|work=Houston Chronicle|last=Fikac|first=Peggy|title=Senators Patrick, Carona make it personal in email spat |date=May 7, 2012|accessdate=May 8, 2012}}</ref><ref name=d_spat>{{cite news|url=http://frontburner.dmagazine.com/2012/05/07/gossip-wars-sens-john-carona-and-dan-patrick/|last=Heid|first=Jason|date=May 7, 2012|accessdate= May 8, 2012|work= D Magazine|title=Gossip Wars: Sens. John Carona and Dan Patrick}}</ref> In an email exchange, Patrick accused Carona of spreading false rumors about Patrick's marriage. Carona denied that, and additionally denied having commented on Patrick's sexuality.<ref name=stateman_spat/><ref name=mysa_spat/><ref name=d_spat/> Carona further said to Patrick: \"I've never been shy about sharing my dislike and distrust of you. Put bluntly, I believe you are a snake oil salesman, a narcissist that would say anything to draw attention to himself.\"<ref name=stateman_spat/><ref name=d_spat/> News reports suggest that the feud was motivated by positioning to succeed David Dewhurst as lieutenant governor should Dewhurst have won a seat as U.S. senator, in 2012.<ref name=stateman_spat/><ref name=mysa_spat/>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* Committee on Education (Chair)\n* Committee on Criminal Justice\n* Committee on Finance\n* Committee on Health & Human Services\n* Committee on Intergovernmental Relations\n* Committee on Finance\n** Subcommittee on Fiscal Matters\n** Subcommittee on Public Education Funding\n** Subcommittee on Higher Education Funding\n\n==Lieutenant governor of Texas==\n===2014 campaign===\n{{See also|2014 Texas elections#Lieutenant Governor}}\nOn June 26, 2013, Patrick announced he would challenge incumbent David Dewhurst in the Republican primary for lieutenant governor in 2014.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hamilton |first=Reeve |url=http://www.texastribune.org/2013/06/27/coming-out-swinging-dan-patrick-announces-lt-gov/ |title=Coming Out Swinging, Dan Patrick Announces for Lt. Gov. |work=The Texas Tribune |date=July 7, 2013 |accessdate=May 1, 2014}}</ref> This challenge came despite Patrick's enthusiastic endorsement of Dewhurst in his failed 2012 bid for the U.S. Senate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.redstate.com/irish067/2012/07/27/joann-fleming-slams-patrick-over-dewhurst-endorsement/ |title=JoAnn Fleming Slams Patrick Over Dewhurst Endorsement |publisher=RedState |accessdate=May 1, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Messamore |first=Andrew |url=http://blog.chron.com/texaspolitics/2012/07/dan-patrick-endorses-dewhurst/ |title=Dan Patrick endorses Dewhurst \u2013 Texas Politics |publisher=Blog.chron.com |date=July 26, 2012 |accessdate=May 1, 2014}}</ref> Patrick stated that while he had been planning on retiring from politics after his Senate term ended, he decided to run for lieutenant governor after Dewhurst failed to end fellow State Senator [[Wendy Davis (politician)|Wendy Davis]]'s filibuster of [[Texas Senate Bill 5]] and after Senator [[Jane Nelson]] refused to run herself.<ref name=\"ChristianFirst\"/>\n\nIn his race for lieutenant governor, Patrick was endorsed in July 2013 by [[Mike Huckabee]], the former [[governor of Arkansas]] who ran unsuccessfully for the [[U.S. presidential election, 2008|2008 Republican presidential nomination]]. In 2012, Huckabee had also endorsed David Dewhurst for the U.S. Senate nomination for the seat vacated by [[Kay Bailey Hutchison]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.chron.com/texaspolitics/2013/07/patrick-touts-huckabee-endorsement/|title=Patrick touts Huckabee endorsement, July 23, 2013|publisher=blog.chron.com|accessdate=July 24, 2013}}</ref> Victory went, however, to the Republican [[Ted Cruz]].\n\nAt a candidate forum in [[College Station, Texas|College Station]] in January 2014, Patrick said that he and two other challengers to Dewhurst, [[Jerry E. Patterson]] and [[Todd Staples]], could have sought re-election in their current positions as [[Texas General Land Office|Land Commissioner]] and [[Texas Commissioner of Agriculture]], respectively, but were instead \"putting our positions on the line because we need new leadership. ... An energetic, passionate conservative to lead the Senate.\"<ref name=incollegestation>{{cite news|url=http://www.theeagle.com/news/local/article_eb860364-bdde-543d-9554-7f4622c89351.html|title=Beth Brown, \"GOP lieutenant governor candidates reach out to Bryan-College Station voters,\" January 9, 2013|newspaper=[[Bryan-College Station Eagle]] |accessdate=January 9, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAt the candidate forum, Patrick described education as a key issue in his campaign because of the 25 percent statewide high school drop-out rate, rising to 40 to 50 percent in the inner cities. He stated that \"we do not have a future in the state of Texas if we have half of the next adult population \u2013 majority being Hispanic \u2013 don't have a high school degree.\"<ref name=incollegestation/> Patrick said that as lieutenant governor, he would work to secure the border with [[Mexico]] and to abolish [[sanctuary cities]] and in-state tuition for illegal immigrants. He also called for lowering [[property tax]]es.<ref name=incollegestation/>\n\nPatrick led the four-candidate field in the primary with 550,769 votes (41.5%). Dewhurst followed with 376,196 (28.3%); Staples, with 235,981 (17.8%), and Patterson, 165,787 (12.5%).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://team1.sos.state.tx.us/enr/results/mar04_169_state.htm?x=0&y=218&id=176 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20140305180619/https://team1.sos.state.tx.us/enr/results/mar04_169_state.htm?x=0&y=218&id=176 |url-status=dead |archive-date=March 5, 2014 |title=Republican primary election returns, March 4, 2014 |publisher=enr.sos.state.tx.us |accessdate=March 5, 2014}}</ref> Election watchers did not expect Patrick to get first place.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Hooks|first1=Christopher|title=The Ascendancy of Dan Patrick|url=https://www.texasobserver.org/ascendancy-dan-patrick/|date=March 5, 2014|magazine=[[The Texas Observer]]|accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref> In the runoff election on May 27, Patrick won with 487,829 votes (65.1%), defeating Dewhurst, who had 262,086 votes (34.9%).<ref name=\"Fernandez2014\">{{cite news|last1=Fernandez|first1=Manny|title=Lieutenant Governor Loses Texas Runoff as Tea Party Holds Sway|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/05/28/us/politics/tea-party-favorite-beats-lieutenant-governor-in-texas.html|date=May 27, 2014|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=January 24, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Stutz|first1=Terrence|last2=Garrett|first2=Robert T.|title=Dan Patrick Wins GOP Nomination for Texas Lieutenant Governor|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/local-politics/2014/05/27/dan-patrick-wins-gop-nomination-for-texas-lieutenant-governor|date=May 27, 2014|newspaper=[[The Dallas Morning News]]|accessdate=January 10, 2018}}</ref> Patrick's victory was one of several notable primary victories by [[Tea Party movement]]-aligned Republicans in the election runoff.<ref name=\"Fernandez2014\"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Grissom|first1=Brandi|title=Tea Party Conservatives Win Top GOP Runoffs|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2014/05/28/tea-party-conservatives-win-top-gop-runoff-contest/|date=May 28, 2014|work=[[The Texas Tribune]]|accessdate=January 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Ross Ramsey of ''[[The Texas Tribune]]'', Patrick did not shift to the political middle as the general election approached, contrary to what political candidates typically do.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ramsey|first1=Ross|title=Analysis: Who\u2019s the Establishment, Anyway?|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2018/01/10/analysis-whos-establishment-anyway/|date=January 10, 2018|work=[[The Texas Tribune]]|accessdate=January 10, 2017}}</ref> On November 4, 2014, Patrick won the general election against his state Senate colleague, [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] [[Leticia Van de Putte]] of [[San Antonio, Texas|San Antonio]], to become the lieutenant governor-elect of Texas.<ref name=geresults/> He was swept into office in a Republican landslide that saw the party retain all statewide elected offices for the fifth consecutive election.\n\n===2018 campaign===\n{{See also|2018 Texas elections#Lieutenant Governor}}\nOn January 9, 2017, the day before the 85th Texas Legislature began its session, Patrick announced he would run for re-election in 2018.<ref name=\"Re-Election2018\">{{cite web|last1=Whitely|first1=Jason|title=Lt. Gov. Patrick Announces Re-Election Campaign|url=http://www.wfaa.com/news/politics/lt-gov-patrick-announces-re-election-campaign/384424961|date=January 9, 2017|publisher=[[WFAA]]|accessdate=January 10, 2017}}</ref> He stated his early announcement was in order to dispel rumors that he would challenge Governor [[Greg Abbott]] or U.S. Senator [[Ted Cruz]].<ref name=\"Re-Election2018\"/> Patrick easily won the Republican primary on March 6, 2018, defeating [[Rockwall, Texas|Rockwall]] City Council Member Scott Milder.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McGaughy|first1=Lauren|title=Lt. Gov. Dan Patrick Shreds GOP Challenger, Will Face Mike Collier in General Election|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/2018-elections/2018/03/06/lt-gov-dan-patrick-shreds-republican-challenger-will-face-mike-collier-november|date=March 6, 2018|newspaper=[[The Dallas Morning News]]|accessdate=March 7, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Walsh|first1=Sean Collins|title=Lt. Gov. Dan Patrick Defeats GOP Challenger Scott Milder|url=https://www.statesman.com/news/state--regional-govt--politics/gov-dan-patrick-defeats-gop-challenger-scott-milder/G0fVSSCSLFS9M2aYvb6lbN/new.html |accessdate=May 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to his own campaign, Patrick was active in endorsing and assisting Republican primary candidates in the Texas Senate, including some challengers to GOP incumbents.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jeffers|first1=Gromer, Jr.|title=Already Playing with a Strong Hand, Lt. Gov. Dan Patrick Gambles by Endorsing in GOP Primaries|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/2018-elections/2018/02/21/already-playing-strong-hand-lt-gov-dan-patrick-gambles-endorsing-gop-primaries|date=February 21, 2018|newspaper=[[The Dallas Morning News]]|accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Prazan|first1=Phil|title=Dan Patrick Picks Sides in GOP Primary Races for the Texas Senate|url=https://www.kxan.com/news/local/austin/dan-patrick-picks-sides-in-gop-primary-races-for-the-texas-senate_20180312075314850/1031474849|date=|publisher=[[KXAN-TV]]|accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref> Patrick's favored candidates won nearly all the races where Patrick made intraparty endorsements.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Formby|first1=Brandon|last2=Greene|first2=Sydney|title=GOP State Sen. Craig Estes Ousted; Sen. Bob Hall Defeats Burkett|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2018/03/06/craig-estes-angela-paxton-bob-hall-texas-senate-primary-2018/|date=March 6, 2018|work=[[The Texas Tribune]]|accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref> Later in the year, Patrick donated nearly $175,000 to Texas Senate candidate [[Pete Flores]] in a special election; Flores won the election in an upset, increasing Patrick's chances of keeping a three-fifths GOP majority in the Senate after the 2018 elections.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McGuinness|first1=Dylan|title=Flores Defeats Gallego in Senate District 19|url=https://www.mysanantonio.com/news/local/article/Polls-close-at-7-p-m-in-Senate-District-19-13239398.php|date=September 19, 2018|newspaper=[[San Antonio Express-News]]|accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Svitek|first1=Patrick|title=Republican Pete Flores Upsets Democrat Pete Gallego in Race for Uresti Seat|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2018/09/18/republican-pete-flores-track-upset-race-democratic-friendly-uresti-sea/|date=September 18, 2018|work=[[The Texas Tribune]]|accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Ratcliffe|first1=R.G.|title=The Texas Democratic Party Has Lost the Ability to Sell Its Brand|url=https://www.texasmonthly.com/politics/texas-democratic-party-lost-ability-sell-brand/|date=September 19, 2018|magazine=[[Texas Monthly]]|accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref> Patrick succeeded in maintaining a three-fifths majority in the Senate, though Republican Senator [[Kel Seliger]] was considered a possible swing-vote.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McGaughy|first1=Lauren|title=Democrats Flip Two Texas Senate Seats, Creating Key GOP Swing Vote in the Process|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/2018-elections/2018/11/07/democrats-flip-two-texas-senate-seats-create-key-gop-swing-vote-process|date=November 7, 2018|newspaper=[[The Dallas Morning News]]|accessdate=November 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the November 6 general election, Patrick won re-election to a second term,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Marfin|first1=Catherine|title=Lt. Gov. Dan Patrick defeats Democrat Mike Collier|url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/news/politics/texas/article/With-much-of-early-vote-counted-Lt-Gov-Dan-13368728.php|date=November 6, 2018|newspaper=[[Houston Chronicle]]|accessdate=November 7, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Cunningham|first1=Chelsea|title=Texas Lt. Gov. Dan Patrick defeats Mike Collier for second term|url=https://www.khou.com/article/news/politics/elections/texas-lt-gov-dan-patrick-defeats-mike-collier-for-second-term/285-612126278|date=November 7, 2018|publisher=[[KHOU]]|accessdate=November 7, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Zdun|first1=Matt|last2=Collier|first2=Kiah|title=Gov. Greg Abbott clinches second term as GOP wins closest statewide races in 20 years|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2018/11/06/greg-abbott-lupe-valdez-dan-patrick-justin-nelson-texas-midterm-2018/|date=November 6, 2018|work=[[The Texas Tribune]]|accessdate=November 7, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Morris|first1=Allie|last2=Zelinski|first2=Andrea|title=Gov. Abbott wins re-election as other statewide Republicans claim victory|url=https://www.chron.com/news/politics/texas/article/Gov-Abbott-wins-re-election-as-other-statewide-13369601.php|date=November 6, 2018|publisher=Chron.com|accessdate=November 7, 2018}}</ref> defeating Democratic nominee Mike Collier. He won about 51% of the vote against Collier's 47%.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://enrpages.sos.state.tx.us/public/nov06_331_state.htm?x=0&y=8370&id=374|title=Election Returns|date=November 6, 2018|publisher=[[Texas Secretary of State]]|accessdate=November 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181108030039/https://enrpages.sos.state.tx.us/public/nov06_331_state.htm?x=0&y=8370&id=374|archive-date=November 8, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\n[[File:Donald Trump Dallas 2017.jpg|thumb|200px|Patrick, third from left, attending an October 2017 meeting with U.S. President Donald Trump, Texas Governor [[Greg Abbott]], and [[Federal Emergency Management Agency|FEMA officials]], on [[Hurricane Harvey]] relief and recovery efforts.]]\nPatrick was sworn in on January 20, 2015.<ref name=nextlevel>Lindell, Chuck (January 20, 2015). [http://www.statesman.com/news/news/dan-patrick-snaps-selfies-vows-next-level-conserva/njr2K/ \"Dan Patrick Snaps Selfies, Vows \u2018Next Level\u2019 Conservatism\"]. ''Austin American -Statesman''. Retrieved January 23, 2015.</ref><ref>Fernandez, Manny (January 20, 2015). [https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/21/us/politics/new-texas-governor-greg-abbott-expected-to-continue-on-perrys-path.html \"Texas\u2019 New Governor Echoes the Plans of Perry\"]. ''The New York Times''. Retrieved January 24, 2015.</ref> Soon after assuming office, the [[Texas Senate]] voted to drop the threshold needed to consider a bill from two-thirds to three-fifths, something that Patrick had long supported.<ref name=\"PartyCrasher\"/><ref>Smith, Morgan (January 21, 2015). [http://www.texastribune.org/2015/01/21/change-procedure-senate-democrats-lose-clout/ \"With Change in Procedure, Senate Democrats Lose Clout\"]. ''The Texas Tribune''. Retrieved January 23, 2015.</ref><ref>Koppel, Nathan (January 21, 2015). [https://www.wsj.com/articles/texas-lt-gov-dan-patrick-moves-quickly-to-advance-conservative-agenda-1421883867 \"Texas Lt. Gov. Dan Patrick Moves Quickly to Advance Conservative Agenda\"]. ''The Wall Street Journal''. Retrieved January 23, 2015.</ref> Under Patrick, the Senate enforced procedural rules that had long been ignored.<ref name=\"AudienceOfOne\"/>\n\nMajor legislation that Patrick helped pass during his tenure as lieutenant governor include legalization of [[Campus carry in the United States|campus carry]]<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Jukam|first1=Kelsey|title=The Winners and Losers of the Battle for Campus Carry |url=https://www.texasobserver.org/the-winners-and-losers-of-the-battle-for-campus-carry/|date=June 3, 2015|magazine=The Texas Observer|accessdate=September 29, 2016}}</ref> and [[Open carry in the United States|open carry]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Gov. Abbott signs open carry, campus carry into law|url=http://www.kvue.com/news/state/gov-abbott-signs-open-carry-campus-carry-into-law/152502166 |date=June 13, 2015|work=KVUE|accessdate=September 29, 2016}}</ref> a bill allowing pastors to refuse marrying couples if it violates their beliefs,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Crampton|first1=Liz|title=Abbott Signs \"Pastor Protection Act\" Into Law |url=https://www.texastribune.org/2015/06/11/gov-abbott-signs-pastor-protection-act/|date=June 11, 2015|work=The Texas Tribune|accessdate=September 29, 2016}}</ref> and expanded border security and enforcement measures.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lieutenant Governor Dan Patrick and the Texas Senate Achieved Your Priorities|url=https://www.ltgov.state.tx.us/priorities/lieutenant-governor-dan-patrick-and-the-texas-senate-achieved-your-priorities/|date=June 10, 2015|publisher=Office of the Lieutenant Governor |accessdate=September 29, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Abbott Signs Budget Into Law |url=http://www.twcnews.com/tx/austin/news/2015/06/21/abbott-signs-budget-into-law.html|date=June 21, 2015|publisher=TWC News |accessdate=September 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\nPatrick made legislation prohibiting state or local governments from issuing subpoenas on pastors' sermons a priority in the 2017 session.<ref name=\"SvitekSubpoenas\"/> Governor Abbott signed the bill into law on May 21, 2017.<ref name=\"SvitekSubpoenas\">{{cite news |last1=Svitek|first1=Patrick|title=Abbott Signs Bill Protecting Sermons from Subpoenas |url=https://www.texastribune.org/2017/05/21/abbott-signs-bill-protecting-sermons-subpoenas/|date=May 21, 2017|work=[[The Texas Tribune]]|accessdate=May 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\n===Abortion===\nPatrick opposes [[abortion]] and supported Texas' \"Mandatory Ultrasound Bill\", a bill signed into law in May 2011 by Governor Perry, which requires women seeking abortion to have a [[Medical ultrasonography|sonogram]] of the [[fetus]] taken at least twenty-four hours before the abortion is performed.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n\nPatrick opposes abortion in cases of incest and rape. In January 2014, when he was asked about exceptions to outlawing abortion, Patrick said, \"The only exception would be if the life of the mother was truly in danger\u2026but that is rare.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mystatesman.com/news/news/local/herman-abortion-exceptionalism-in-the-gop-lite-guv/ndC75/#e5ff2779.3657224.735464|title=Herman: Abortion exceptionalism in the GOP lite guv primary |publisher=Mystatesman.com |accessdate=January 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Education===\nPatrick supports increasing the number of [[charter schools]] in the state.<ref name=Nov2010PressRelease />\n\nIn February 2011, Patrick, who at the time was vice chairman of the Texas senate's [[Texas Senate#Committee Structure|Committee on Education]], spoke in favor of cutting an unspecified number of non-teaching positions from the state's public school districts, citing positions such as \"math department supervisors\" or \"curriculum experts\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.texastribune.org/texas-education/public-education/do-texas-schools-spend-too-much-on-administration/ |title=Do Texas Schools Spend Too Much on Administration? |work=The Texas Tribune |date=February 25, 2011 |first=Morgan |last=Smith |accessdate=November 4, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.senate.state.tx.us/75r/senate/commit/c530/c530_81.htm |title=Committee Information for 81st Session's Senate Committee on Education |publisher=Texas State Senate |accessdate=November 4, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026014521/http://www.senate.state.tx.us/75r/senate/commit/c530/c530_81.htm |archivedate=October 26, 2012}}</ref>  At the time, Patrick cited a statistic later determined to be misleading by PolitiFact.com that Texas's 1,200+ public school districts, considered as a group, are the fifth-largest employer in the world.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.politifact.com/texas/statements/2011/mar/11/dan-patrick/dan-patrick-says-texas-school-districts-all-told-a/ |title=Mostly False: Dan Patrick Says Texas school districts are the fifth largest employers in the world. |work=PolitiFact.com |accessdate=November 4, 2012}}</ref>\n\nPatrick is on record as determined to establish [[creationism]] within the public school curriculum in Texas, despite court rulings that such a policy would violate the [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/bad_astronomy/2014/01/29/creationism_and_texas_once_more_into_the_breach_of_education.html|title=Creationism and Texas: Once more into the breach of education.|work=Slate Magazine|accessdate=January 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Patrick pushed to increase Texas teachers' paychecks by $5,000.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Swaby|first1=Aliyya|title=Educators have been skeptical of Dan Patrick. Will they support his teacher pay raise plan?|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2019/02/25/texas-lt-gov-dan-patrick-unpopular-texas-teachers-will-his-teacher-pay/|date=February 25, 2019|work=[[The Texas Tribune]]|accessdate=March 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Swaby|first1=Aliyya|title=Texas teacher pay emerges as a sticking point between House and Senate |url=https://www.texastribune.org/2019/03/05/texas-teacher-pay-emerges-sticking-point-between-house-and-senate/|date=March 6, 2019 |work=[[The Texas Tribune]]|accessdate=March 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Gun laws===\nIn 2019, Patrick called for requiring background checks for gun sales between two strangers.<ref>{{cite news | last1=Axelrod | first1=Tal | title=Texas Lt. Gov: 'Stranger-to-stranger' gun sales should require background check | url=https://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/460297-texas-lt-gov-stranger-to-stranger-gun-sales-should-require-background | date=September 6, 2019 | newspaper=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] | accessdate=September 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine | last1=Brest | first1=Mike | title=Texas Lt. Gov. says he's going to defy NRA and work to close background check loopholes | url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/texas-lt-gov-says-hes-going-to-defy-nra-and-work-to-close-background-check-loopholes | date=September 6, 2019 | magazine=[[Washington Examiner]] | accessdate=September 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Shaw | first1=Adam | title=Texas Lt. Gov. Dan Patrick \u2018willing to take an arrow\u2019 in bucking NRA on background checks | url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/texas-lt-gov-dan-patrick-says-hes-willing-to-take-an-arrow-as-he-bucks-nra-on-background-checks | date=September 7, 2019 | publisher=[[Fox News]] | accessdate=September 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Illegal immigration===\nPatrick opposes [[Illegal immigration to the United States|illegal immigration]]. As a talk radio host, he reserved some of his \"most hard-edged oratory for illegal immigrants.\"<ref name=\"PartyCrasher\"/> Patrick expressed support for [[Arizona SB 1070|Arizona's SB 1070 immigration enforcement law]], and supports passing a similar law in Texas that would allow local law enforcement to ask lawfully-stopped individuals about their immigration status and would make it a state misdemeanor to be present in Texas as an illegal immigrant.<ref name=Nov2010PressRelease>{{cite web|url=http://www.senate.state.tx.us/75r/senate/members/dist7/pr10/p110810a.htm |title=Press Release from the Office of State Senator Dan Patrick: Senator Dan Patrick Files Conservative Agenda |publisher=Texas State Senate |date=November 8, 2010 |accessdate=November 4, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130112152211/http://www.senate.state.tx.us/75r/senate/members/dist7/pr10/p110810a.htm |archivedate=January 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAs Lieutenant Governor, Patrick moved to keep [[National Guard of the United States|National Guard]] troops sent to the Texas-Mexico border during the illegal immigration surge of 2014 indefinitely, rather than until March 2015, as originally planned.<ref name=Natguard>The Associated Press (February 10, 2015) \u2013 [http://dfw.cbslocal.com/2015/02/10/lt-gov-patrick-national-guard-not-leaving-texas-border/ \"Lt. Gov. Patrick: National Guard Not Leaving Texas Border\"]. ''CBS-DFW''. Retrieved February 10, 2015.</ref> Patrick's 2015 budget in the [[Texas Senate]] called for spending $815 million on border security, which he said was more than the previous seven years combined.<ref name=Natguard/> Governor [[Greg Abbott]] signed the measure\u2014for about $800 million\u2014into law.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Garrett|first1=Robert T.|title=Abbott Wields Veto Pen to Trim Nearly $300 Million from Texas Budget |url=http://www.dallasnews.com/news/politics/2015/06/20/abbott-wields-veto-pen-to-trim-300-million-from-texas-budget|date=June 20, 2015|newspaper=[[The Dallas Morning News]]|accessdate=December 19, 2016}}</ref> In a June 2018 interview on [[Fox Business Network]], Patrick estimated that 30 million illegal immigrants lived in the U.S.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Giaritelli|first1=Anna|title=As Many as 30 Million People Live in US Illegally, Says Texas Lt. Gov. Dan Patrick|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/as-many-as-30-million-people-live-in-us-illegally-says-texas-lt-gov-dan-patrick|date=June 22, 2018|magazine=[[The Washington Examiner]] |accessdate=July 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Same-sex marriage and LGBT issues===\nOn February 26, 2014, following a federal court ruling the Texas ban on same-sex marriage unconstitutional, Patrick asserted his position that marriage is a union between one man and one woman. He then further stated his intentions to fight such decisions should he be elected to the Lt. Governor's office.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/DanPatrick/status/438782159138979840 |title=Twitter / DanPatrick: I want to re-emphasize my long |publisher=Twitter.com |date=February 26, 2014 |accessdate=May 1, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/DanPatrick/status/438761650137493504 |title=Twitter / DanPatrick: As Lieutenant Governor I'll |publisher=Twitter.com |date=February 26, 2014 |accessdate=May 1, 2014}}</ref>\n\nPatrick strongly opposed HERO, an unsuccessful [[Houston]] ordinance intended to establish legal protections for gay and transgender residents along with some other classes, as he claimed that the ordinance would lead to sexual predators being freely able to enter women's restrooms.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Driessen|first1=Katherine|title=Patrick takes aim at HERO, mayor |url=http://www.houstonchronicle.com/news/article/Dan-Patrick-takes-aim-at-HERO-mayor-6578348.php|accessdate=May 14, 2016 |newspaper=[[The Houston Chronicle]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Ura|first1=Alexa|title=Bathroom Fears Flush Houston Discrimination Ordinance|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2015/11/03/houston-anti-discrimination-ordinance-early-voting/|date=November 3, 2015|work=[[The Texas Tribune]]|accessdate=May 14, 2016}}</ref> Patrick has stated that if necessary, he would support legislation to require people to use the bathroom that corresponds to the gender listed on their birth certificates.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ward|first1=Mike|last2=Hinchliffe|first2=Emma|title=Patrick Says He Would Support a State Transgender Bathroom Law |url=http://www.houstonchronicle.com/news/politics/texas/article/Patrick-says-he-would-support-a-state-transgender-7377531.php |date=April 26, 2016|newspaper=[[The Houston Chronicle]]|accessdate=May 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHours after the [[2016 Orlando nightclub shooting]], Patrick tweeted a picture of the Bible verse, \"Do not be deceived: God cannot be mocked. A man reaps what he sows. Galatians 6:7.\" An adviser released a statement that the tweet had been pre-scheduled, and the tweet was later deleted.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hamilton|first1=Jessica|title=Texas Lt. Gov. Dan Patrick deletes \"reap what you sow\" tweet after mass shooting at LGBT club|url=http://www.chron.com/news/article/Texas-Lt-Governor-Dan-Patrick-tweets-reap-what-8076147.php |date=June 12, 2016|newspaper=[[The Houston Chronicle]]|accessdate=June 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Blakemore |first1=Allen|title=Statement Regarding Orlando Tragedy and Twitter and Facebook Post |url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/315502915/PR-16-06-12|date=June 12, 2016|accessdate=June 12, 2016}}</ref> Patrick issued a statement on the incident, again stating that the tweet was pre-planned and that \"I didn\u2019t pull down the FB post & tweet because God\u2019s word is wrong. His word is never wrong ... I took it down to stop the hateful comments and the misinformation being spread of God\u2019s message to all of us- straight or gay.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Patrick|first1=Dan|title=My Facebook Statement Regarding This Morning\u2019s Bible Verse Post|url=http://danpatrick.org/facebook-statement-regarding-mornings-bible-verse-post/ |website=danpatrick.org|accessdate=December 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2016, Patrick criticized the [[Obama administration]] after it released a directive stating that all public schools must allow transgender students to use the bathroom and locker facilities that correspond with their identified gender, stating that, on the prospect of the federal government withholding funding for Texas schools for not following the directive, \"he can keep his 30 pieces of silver [and that w]e will not yield to blackmail from the president of the United States.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2016/05/transgender-bathrooms-obama-texas-lieutenant-governor-223159|title=Texas Lt. Gov. Accuses Obama of 'Blackmail' on Transgender Bathrooms|last1=Gass|first1=Nick|date=May 13, 2016 |publisher=[[Politico]]|accessdate=May 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/05/14/us/transgender-bathrooms.html|title=Solace and Fury as Schools React to Transgender Policy|last1=Healy|first1=Jack|last2=P\u00e9rez-Pe\u00f1amay |first2=Richard|date=May 13, 2016|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=May 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://insider.foxnews.com/2016/05/13/tx-lt-gov-dan-patrick-transgender-bathrooms-would-be-end-public-education|title=Texas to Instruct Schools Not to Obey Obama's Transgender Bathroom Decree |accessdate=May 14, 2016|publisher=Fox News Insider}}</ref> In 2017, Patrick strongly advocated for a [[bathroom bill]] that would prohibit transgender students at public schools from using any restroom other than that of their biological sex.<ref name=\"ToughFight\" /> Patrick described the legislation as a \"legislative priority.\"<ref name=\"ToughFight\" /> Patrick encouraged state Senator [[Lois Kolkhorst]] of [[Brenham, Texas|Brenham]] to introduce a [[bathroom bill]] similar to a [[Public Facilities Privacy & Security Act|previous law adopted in 2016]] in [[North Carolina]], and strongly pushed for it at its proposal on January 5, 2017.<ref name=\"ToughFight\">{{cite news|last1=Svitek|first1=Patrick|title=With Bathroom Bill, Texas Lt. Gov. Dan Patrick Plows into \"Tough Fight\" |url=https://www.texastribune.org/2017/01/07/bathroom-bill-patrick-plows-tough-fight/|date=January 7, 2017|work=[[The Texas Tribune]]|accessdate=January 10, 2017}}</ref> [[Speaker of the Texas House of Representatives|Texas House Speaker]] [[Joe Straus]] of [[San Antonio, Texas|San Antonio]], a [[Factions in the Republican Party (United States)#Moderate wing|moderate Republican]], said that the measure is not an important matter for lower chamber.<ref name=\"ToughFight\"/><ref>Bobby Cervantes, \"Bathroom legislation now ready for debate: Bruising battle looms over transgender bill\", ''[[San Antonio Express-News]]'', January 6, 2016, pp. 1, A11</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, Patrick called Democratic presidential candidate Beto O'Rourke \"light in the loafers\", a slur often used to insinuate someone as gay, though O'Rourke is heterosexual. Patrick also called O'Rourke a \"moron.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/houston/article/Lt-Gov-Dan-Patrick-Beto-O-Rourke-is-light-13806867.php|title=Texas Lt. Gov. Dan Patrick: Beto O\u2019Rourke is \u2018light in the loafers\u2019|last=Andrea Zelinski|date=April 30, 2019|website=Houston Chronicle|access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|first1=Zack|last1=Budryk|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/media/441396-texas-lt-governor-calls-beto-orourke-a-moron|title=Texas Lt. Governor calls Beto O'Rourke a 'moron'|website=The Hill|date=April 30, 2019 |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref> Patrick later stated that while he stood by his comments, the insinuation was unintentional.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/DanPatrick/status/1123276995171844096|title=I stand by my remarks on @FoxNews that @BetoORourke is a lightweight with no public policy substance. His views on the border are ridiculous. If anyone took a different meaning from one of my comments, I apologize.  Let me reiterate \u2014 it was not intended.|first=Dan|last=Patrick|date=April 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Marijuana===\nPatrick has advocated against bills that would reduce criminal penalties for marijuana possession. He has expressed skepticism of medical marijuana legalization.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2019/04/30/texas-senate-marijuana-decriminalization-dan-patrick-joe-moody/|title=Texas Lt. Gov. Dan Patrick says Senate won't pass bill to lower penalties for marijuana |last=Tribune |first=The Texas|last2=Samuels|first2=Alex|date=2019-04-30|website=The Texas Tribune|access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref>\n\n===Domestic partner benefits===\nIn November 2012, Patrick asked [[Texas Attorney General|Texas attorney general]] [[Greg Abbott]]'s office to issue an opinion on the constitutionality of government entities providing domestic partner insurance benefits. An [[Texas Proposition 2 (2005)|amendment to the Texas Constitution]] in 2005 limits marriage to heterosexual relationships and prohibits similar, alternative legal arrangements. Patrick did not disclose his own views on [[same-sex marriage]] or [[civil union]]s for same-sex couples. He told the ''[[Houston Chronicle]]'' that his request was prompted by [[Dallas County, Texas|Dallas County's]] November 2012 decision and an [[Pflugerville Independent School District|Austin-area public school district's]] October 2012 decision to join other Texas cities and counties in extending benefits to their unmarried employees' heterosexual or homosexual partners.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/houston/article/Patrick-questions-legality-of-domestic-4004790.php |last=Hassan |first=Anita |date=November 2, 2012 |accessdate=November 4, 2012 |title=Sen. Patrick questions legality of domestic partnership benefits |work=Houston Chronicle}}</ref>\n\n===Statutory rape laws===\nPatrick was interviewed extensively on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s ''[[20/20 (US television series)|20/20]]'' segment \"The Age of Consent: When Young Love Is a Sex Crime,\" defending his position favoring very tough Texas [[statutory rape]] laws. \"While it seems unfair, he was 19, she was 15,\" says Patrick, \"That's the price you pay. Even if you end up getting married.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=John |last=Stossel |author2=Gena Binkley |author3=Andrew G. Sullivan |title=The Age of Consent: When Young Love Is a Sex Crime |url=http://abcnews.go.com/print?id=4400537 |work=ABC News |publisher=ABCNews Internet Ventures |date=March 7, 2008 |accessdate=July 19, 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Confederate monuments===\nPatrick is a strong supporter of maintaining [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] monuments on public display, despite opposition from civil rights groups who consider the statues as a defense of the institution of [[slavery]]. As one of six members of the board that oversees the [[Texas State Capitol]] grounds, Patrick described the need: \"to learn from history all of our history, including events and times that many would like to forget. ... Our goal should be to have a meaningful dialogue for future generations so those moments in our history are not repeated.\"<ref>Allie Morris, \"Austin has a monumental problem: Confederate icons have backing at the Capitol,\" ''San Antonio Express-News,''  August 17, 2017, pp. 1, A6.</ref>\n\n===Coronavirus comments===\n{{further|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Texas}}\nIn an interview with Fox News host [[Tucker Carlson]] on March 23, 2020, Patrick stated that he was willing to risk his life from the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]] if it would avoid an economic shutdown, which he stated would negatively impact subsequent generations. Patrick also stated that he thought many grandparents agreed with him on this.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/489162-texas-lt-gov-grandparents-dont-want-the-whole-country-to-be-sacrificed|title=Texas lt gov: Grandparents 'don't want the whole country to be sacrificed' amid coronavirus closures|first=Aris|last=Folley|date=March 23, 2020|website=The Hill}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/public-health/2020/03/24/texas-lt-gov-dan-patrick-spurns-shelter-in-place-urges-return-to-work-says-grandparents-should-sacrifice/|title=Texas Lt. Gov. Dan Patrick spurns shelter in place, urges return to work, says grandparents should sacrifice|date=March 24, 2020|website=Dallas News}}</ref>\n\n=== Video games ===\nAfter the [[2019 El Paso shooting]], Patrick listed factors that he believed contributed to the shooting, starting off with video games, saying, \"We've always had guns, always had evil, but I see a video game industry that teaches young people to kill.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2019/08/04/dan-patrick-video-games-el-paso-shooting/|title=After El Paso shooting, Texas Lt. Gov. Dan Patrick says video games teach young people \"to kill\"|last=Rocha|first=Alana|date=August 4, 2019|website=The Texas Tribune|language=en|access-date=August 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Presidential politics===\n{{See also|2016 United States presidential election in Texas}}\nPatrick endorsed Texas Senator [[Ted Cruz]] for the [[Republican Party presidential primaries, 2016|2016 Republican presidential primaries]] and served as his Texas [[Ted Cruz presidential campaign, 2016|campaign]] chairman.<ref>{{cite web|title=Texas' Lt. Gov. Now Backing Ted Cruz's Campaign for President|url=http://www.twcnews.com/tx/austin/politics/2015/10/26/lt--gov--dan-patrick-named-texas-chairman-of-ted-cruz-for-president-campaign.html|date=October 26, 2015|publisher=TWC News|accessdate=September 29, 2015}}</ref> After businessman [[Donald Trump]] became the Republican nominee, Patrick endorsed Trump and eventually became the Texas state chairman for [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|his campaign]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Svitek|first1=Patrick|title=Lt. Gov. Dan Patrick Named Trump's Texas Chairman|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2016/09/16/patrick-named-trumps-texas-state-chairman/ |date=September 16, 2016|work=The Texas Tribune|accessdate=September 29, 2016}}</ref> Trump won Texas by 9 percentage points, the closest result since [[United States presidential election in Texas, 1996|1996]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Svitek |first1=Patrick |title=Donald Trump's Shocking Upset Emboldens Texas GOP|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2016/11/09/trumps-impact-texas-gop-unlikely-soon-fade/|date=November 9, 2016|work=[[The Texas Tribune]]|accessdate=December 19, 2016}}</ref> In January 2018, Patrick stated that he considered Presidents Trump and [[Ronald Reagan]] as the two greatest presidents in his lifetime,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wallace|first1=Jeremy|title=Dan Patrick: Trump is Greatest President Since Reagan |url=http://www.chron.com/news/politics/texas/article/Trump-one-of-the-two-greatest-presidents-since-12481441.php|date=January 8, 2018 |newspaper=[[Houston Chronicle]]|accessdate=January 8, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Chang|first1=Julie|title=Lt. Gov. Patrick: Trump Joins Reagan Among Best Presidents|url=http://www.statesman.com/news/state--regional-govt--politics/gov-patrick-trump-joins-reagan-among-best-presidents/0qURfZmAW2EdYyibcbjuVO/|date=January 9, 2018|newspaper=[[Austin American-Statesman]] |accessdate=January 9, 2018}}</ref> and the ''[[Austin American-Statesman]]'' described Patrick as an \"ardent defender\" of Trump.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fikac|first1=Peggy|title=Lt. Gov. Dan Patrick is Trump\u2019s Top Texas Cheerleader |url=http://www.expressnews.com/news/news_columnists/peggy_fikac/article/Lt-Gov-Dan-Patrick-is-Trump-s-top-Texas-12496984.php |date=January 14, 2018|newspaper=[[Austin American-Statesman]]|accessdate=January 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAt a political rally for President Trump on October 17, 2019, Patrick told a crowd of 20,000 that liberals \u201care not our opponents, they are our enemy.\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/18/us/politics/trump-presidency.html|title=On Day 1,001, Trump Made It Clear: Being \u2018Presidential\u2019 Is Boring|last=Baker|first=Peter|date=2019-10-18|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-10-18|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPatrick's first marriage ended in divorce. His second wife is Janetlea \"Jan\" Patricia Rankin, a former [[teacher]]. The couple was married in 1975 and lives in the Houston suburb of [[Cypress, Texas|Cypress]]. They have two children, [[Ryan Patrick|Ryan]] and Shane.<ref name=Jan2007TexasMonthlyArticle /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.patrick.senate.state.tx.us/ |title=The Texas State Senate: District 7 |publisher=Texas State Senate |accessdate=November 4, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026212419/http://www.patrick.senate.state.tx.us/ |archivedate=October 26, 2012}}</ref> Ryan served as a district judge from [[Harris County, Texas]], and swore in his father in 2015, for his term as lieutenant governor of Texas.<ref name=nextlevel/> In July 2017, Ryan Patrick was chosen to be [[United States Attorney|U.S. Attorney]] for the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of Texas|Southern District of Texas]] by U.S. President [[Donald Trump]], and the [[United States Senate]] subsequently confirmed him.\n\n===Religious views===\nWhile growing up, Patrick and his family were \"not very religious.\"<ref name=\"ChristianFirst\">{{cite news|last1=Tilove|first1=Jonathan |title=As Lieutenant Governor, Dan Patrick Remains a 'Christian First'|url=http://www.mystatesman.com/news/state--regional-govt--politics/lieutenant-governor-dan-patrick-remains-christian-first/K53MlGMem1cZSfC2rPe4XJ/|date=April 4, 2015|newspaper=[[Austin American-Statesman]]|accessdate=December 28, 2017}}</ref> After moving to Houston, he and his wife attended a Catholic church,<ref name=\"ChristianFirst\"/> but he joined a Baptist church soon after learning about it.<ref name=Jan2007TexasMonthlyArticle/> Though Patrick was a member of the [[Second Baptist Church Houston]] since 1992, he stated he was not truly a Christian until March 1994, when, on a television-and-radio convention in [[Las Vegas]], he repented of his sins, committed his life to God, and was saved.<ref name=Jan2007TexasMonthlyArticle/><ref name=\"AudienceOfOne\">{{cite news|last1=Walsh|first1=Sean Collins |title=Playing to an Audience of One, Dan Patrick Doesn\u2019t Need Your Approval|url=https://www.mystatesman.com/news/state--regional-govt--politics/playing-audience-one-dan-patrick-doesn-need-your-approval/SCZ3uqoz7sXdstOYvXyxcP/|date=February 16, 2018 |newspaper=[[Austin American-Statesman]]|accessdate=March 6, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"ChristianFirst\"/> After this, Patrick's faith became an important part of his life,<ref name=Jan2007TexasMonthlyArticle/> and he considered going into Christian ministry for a time.<ref name=\"ChristianFirst\"/>\n\nPatrick, an [[Evangelicalism|evangelical Christian]], is a member of various Christian organizations, including [[Fellowship of Christian Athletes]] and the [[International Bible Society]],<ref name=\"VoteSmart\">{{cite web|title=Dan Patrick's Biography|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/57986/dan-patrick#.WFgdA2wzVPY|publisher=[[Project Vote Smart]]|accessdate=December 19, 2016}}</ref> and has served as guest pastor of his church, the [[Second Baptist Church Houston]].<ref name=\"VoteSmart\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Meet Dan|url=http://danpatrick.org/meet-dan/|website=danpatrick.org|accessdate=December 18, 2017}}</ref> He is very outspoken about his Christian faith,<ref name=\"PartyCrasher\"/><ref name=\"ChristianFirst\"/> and he stated in his inauguration speech upon becoming lieutenant governor that \"I respect all faiths and religions, but I am a Christian first, a conservative second and a Republican third, and I praise Jesus for this moment and this day.\"<ref name=nextlevel/> Patrick was baptized in the [[Jordan River]] during a trip to [[Israel]] in 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wise|first1=Hannah|title=Texas Lt. Gov. Dan Patrick Baptized in Jordan River During Visit to Israel|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/politics/2016/05/01/texas-lt-gov-dan-patrick-baptized-in-jordan-river-during-visit-to-israel|date=May 1, 2016|newspaper=[[The Dallas Morning News]]|accessdate=February 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n===2014===\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title=Texas lieutenant gubernatorial election, 2014<ref name=geresults>{{cite web|url=https://team1.sos.state.tx.us/enr/results/nov04_175_state.htm |title=Office of the Secretary of State 2014 General Election Election Night Returns |publisher=Texas Secretary of State |accessdate=December 29, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141105175126/https://team1.sos.state.tx.us/enr/results/nov04_175_state.htm |archivedate=November 5, 2014 }}</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Dan Patrick\n  |votes      = 2,718,406\n  |percentage = 58.13\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = [[Leticia Van de Putte]]\n  |votes      = 1,810,720\n  |percentage = 38.72\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = Libertarian Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Robert Butler\n  |votes      = 119,581\n  |percentage = 2.55\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = Green Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Chandra Courtney\n  |votes      = 27,651\n  |percentage = 0.59\n}}\n{{Election box majority no change\n  |votes      = 907,686\n  |percentage = 19.41%\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n  |votes      = 4,676,358\n  |percentage = 100\n}}\n{{Election box turnout no change\n  |votes      =\n  |percentage = 33.34\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link no change\n  |winner     = Republican Party (United States)\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = Republican primary runoff results, May 27, 2014:  [[List of lieutenant governors of Texas|Lieutenant Governor of Texas]]<ref>[https://team1.sos.state.tx.us/enr/results/may27_173_state.htm]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140529052345/https://team1.sos.state.tx.us/enr/results/may27_173_state.htm |date=May 29, 2014 }}</ref> \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party